1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rc8f5] The Semi-Slav
defense is among the most popular openings for black against 1.d4. It is very
flexible and usually leads to complex play in the middlegame. The name of the
opening is logical since with 4...e6 black is playing a mix between the Slav
and Queen's gambit declined (QGD). As we explained in the introduction to Slav
defense, black generally likes to put his light-squared bishop out to c8-h3
diagonal in the Slav, but in the Semi-Slav this is not the case as it usually
goes to b7.} {White has several promising opening schemes against the
Semi-Slav. Two most popular ones are} 5. e3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gf1c4]} ({and} 5.
Bg5 {[%csl Rc4] in QGD style. Here white needs to be ready for, among other
things, some sharp theoretical battles in the Botvinnik variation:} dxc4 6. e4
b5 7. e5 h6 8. Bh4 g5 {and I think there is no need for that if white can play
for advantage in calmer lines with 5.e3.}) ({Two interesting alternatives are} 
5. g3 {[%csl Rc4]}) ({and} 5. Qb3 {[%csl Gc4]}) 5... Nbd7 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gb7b5,
Gc8b7,Ga7a6,Rc6c5] By accepting such seemingly passive knight development,
black invites white into the famous Meran variation. He wants to take on c4,
play b5, Bb7, a6 and push c5, thereby getting an improved version of QGA. This
has proved to be one of the most reliable opening schemes for black.} ({The
main alternative is} 5... a6 {[%csl Yb8][%cal Gd5c4,Gb7b5,Gc6c5,Gc8b7,Yb8c6]
with a similar idea, only reserving the option of developing the knight to c6
in some positions. We will discuss the most principled reply for white} 6. b3
Bb4 7. Bd2 {in CHAPTER 1.}) {Against this, I propose the Anti-Meran variation}
6. Qc2 {which, as its name suggests,} ({avoids the Meran variation:} 6. Bd3
dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {The Meran variation has a long history and tons of opening
theory, while Anti-Meran became popular much later (during later part of
Anatoly Karpov's career) and thus is a bit less explored. 6.Qc2 discourages
black from taking on c4 as this would be a clear improvement over the Meran -
we would get the same position, but only with white queen on c2 rather than on
d1.}) {Thus black waits for white to play with his bishop before he takes on
c4, so the most popular move is simple} 6... Bd6 ({However, black has a few
other options, such as} 6... b6 {discussed in CHAPTER 2} 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. b3 Be7
9. O-O O-O 10. Bb2 {Is the main line.}) ({and sidelines such as} 6... g6) (6...
a6) ({and} 6... Bb4 {which are covered in CHAPTER 3.}) {Here white has several
good continuations. I propose the most natural one} 7. Bd3 {[%cal Gc2h7,Ge1g1]}
O-O 8. O-O {and we reach the starting position of the Anti-Meran. Black
usually play according to the general plan:} dxc4 ({Though a serious
alternative exists in} 8... e5 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. e4 $1 {which is a topic of
CHAPTER 4.}) ({How to get advantage against minor alternatives:} 8... h6) (8...
Qe7) (8... a6) ({and} 8... Re8 {is explained in CHAPTER 5.}) 9. Bxc4 {Again,
black has a wide choice of options. Most people continue with the
afore-mentioned plan:} b5 ({But black can also play} 9... e5 {[%cal Gc8g4] and
we will see how to fight it with} 10. h3 {in CHAPTER 6}) ({In CHAPTER 7
another major line} 9... a6 {is covered. Here we have an interesting main line
that goes like this:} 10. Rd1 b5 11. Bd3 Qc7 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc6c5]} 12. Bd2
c5 13. Ne4 c4 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Be2 Bb7 16. b3 {where white has can prove the
advantage, in my opinion.}) ({All other alternatives on 9th move including:} 
9... Qe7) (9... c5) (9... Qc7) ({and} 9... h6 {are dealt with in CHAPTER 8.})
10. Be2 {It is difficult to say which bishop retreat is better, this one} ({or
} 10. Bd3) 10... Bb7 {[%cal Gb7g2,Gc6c5] This is the main line according to
the current state of theory.} ({In CHAPTER 9 we will talk about the
alternatives} 10... a6 11. Ng5 $5) (10... Qe7) ({and} 10... Qc7) {In CHAPTER
10 we will explore a relatively rare, but promising idea:} 11. e4 e5 12. dxe5
Nxe5 13. Nh4 $5 {[%csl Rb7,Rd6][%cal Gf2f4,Gh4f5]} *

