1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 a6 {This variation, once
Alekhine's favorite, is the main alternative to the usual 5...Nbd7. The
purpose of a6 is to prepare of dxc4, b7-b5 and c6-c5, transposing into QGA
type of position. This plan works especially well if white wastes a tempo with
his bishop (i.e. Bd3). Another typical middlegame black can go for, instead of
QGA, is the Tarrasch with immediate c6-c5, usually leading either to isolated
queen's pawn (IQP) or hanging pawns type of position. In such positions, black
knight feels more at home on c6 than d7, which is another benefit of not
having played Nbd7. All in all, this is a sensible and very solid variation,
which was even used as the main weapon by Anand in his 2012 Wch match against
Boris Gelfand.} {White has a plenty of good possibilites: 6.c5, 6.Qc2, 6.Bd3
etc. The one I would recommend is} 6. b3 {which curbs black's dxc4 Bxc4 b5
plan since white can now retake on c4 with the pawn. Black can, however, take
advantage of the temporary weakness of Nc3 with} Bb4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb4e1]} (
{Black have also tried the "Tarrasch" plan:} 6... c5 {Here white should play}
7. Bb2 (7. cxd5 {is less precise because of} cxd4 $1) 7... cxd4 ({If} 7... Nc6
{we get a typical Tarrasch after} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Be2 Be6 10. O-O Bd6 11. dxc5
Bxc5 12. Rc1 $14 {as in 1-0 (50) Cheparinov,I (2669)-Zhukova,N (2412) AZE 2011
White faced no obstacles in taking control of important squares d4 and c5:} Qe7
13. Na4 Bd6 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 O-O 16. Nc5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4]} Rac8 17. Nd3 Ba3
18. Nf4 Bxb2 19. Qxb2 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5,Re6] This kind of position will be
examined thoroughly in CHAPTER 3. I give the remainder of this game for
instructive purposes, that is, how white should play in this kind of position:}
h6 20. Bd3 Rfd8 21. h3 Nd7 22. Rfd1 Qf6 23. Qxf6 Nxf6 24. f3 Kf8 25. Kf2 Ke7
26. g4 $1 Rxc1 27. Rxc1 Rc8 28. Rd1 Rc5 29. h4 Ne8 30. Ne2 Nd6 31. Nd4 Rc3 32.
Ke1 $1 {[%cal Ge1d2]} Bd7 33. Kd2 Rc5 34. Rg1 $1 $36 {[%cal Gg4g5]} Ra5 35. a4
Rc5 36. g5 hxg5 $2 {A blunder.} 37. Rxg5 g6 38. e4 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5][%cal
