1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] For
people who like to give names to variations in the openings, this modest move
aiming to develop black's problematic bishop as soon as possible could be
called "Dreev variation". Alexey Dreev is the strongest player who has
employed this variation regularly, though Gregory Kaidanov and other Russian
GMs have also contributed to the early theory of the variation.} 7. Bd3 {Not
the only move here, but development of the bishop to d3 is consistent with our
play in other lines of the Semi-slav.} Bb7 8. O-O Be7 {[%csl Gb7,Ge7] This is
the main premise of this variation. Black's development is more restrained
compared to the main line where he puts this bishop to d6 and plays dxc4 and
b7-b5 followed by Bb7. Yet, modesty is sometimes a virtue and in this
variation black avoids making weaknesses and hopes to equalize gradually,
rather than immediately.} ({The main alternative for black is} 8... dxc4 $5 9.
Bxc4 c5 {which is quite different from positions we will see in the remaining
of the chapter. It is less of a Slav position and more akin to QGA positions
where the center clears up fast and active piece play becomes essential. Even
though it seems principally illogical for black to open up the center while
the kingside is underdeveloped, this side line is surprisingly solid. Even
Magnus Carlsen gave it a go.} 10. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] Logical.} Be7 {I found GM
Shankland's favorite to be the most stubborn move. It turns out that white can
not profit too much from his domination on the d-file and black can fearlessly
continue with his kingside development.} ({If black wishes to avoid any
shenanigans on the d-file, he should play} 10... Qc8 11. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4,
Ge2c4] Preparing e3-e4.} a6 12. e4 cxd4 (12... b5 13. Bb3 c4 $6 {is a typical
overextension in QGA that gives white a free hand in the center.} 14. Bc2 $36 {
[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Gd4d5]}) 13. Nxd4 Bb4 (13... b5 14. Bb3 b4 $2 {would be
another overly optimistic pawn push, punished by} 15. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Re8]} exd5
16. exd5+ Kd8 17. Bg5 $40 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gd4c6] etc.}) 14. f3 {[%csl Rb7,Ge4,Gf3]
It is important to remember this pawn structure as we will see it in another
line. The position is somewhat symmetrical and solid for black, but white has
more active pieces, which gives him a small edge. In addition, the pawn chain
g2-f3-e4 seriously limits the scope of Bb7.} O-O 15. Be3 b5 16. Bb3 $14 {The
pawn can not be taken:} Bxc3 $2 17. bxc3 Qxc3 {due to the typical tactical
shot in such positions:} 18. Nxe6 $1 {[%csl Rd7,Ge6]} fxe6 19. Bxe6+ Rf7 20.
Bd4 Qa3 21. e5 $18 {and black can resign.}) ({but not} 10... Qc7 $6 {[%csl Rc7]
as the queen is not safe here} 11. e4 $1 cxd4 12. Nb5 $36) ({Finally, black
can force the IQP type of position with} 10... cxd4 11. exd4 {[%csl Re8][%cal
Gd4d5,Gc1g5] although this is perhaps the least favorable thing he can do
since it opens up the position even more for white pieces.} Rc8 (11... Bxf3 12.
gxf3 {We know from the Classical Slav that white should not fear doubling
these pawns if he has the initiative.} Bd6 13. d5 $1 {Thematic.} e5 (13... exd5
$2 {would be suicidal} 14. Bxd5 $1 Nxd5 15. Rxd5 Nf6 16. Bg5 $18 {[%csl Rd8,
Re8]}) 14. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8,Gc3e4,Gc4b5]} h6 15. Bh4 g5 16. Bg3 a6 17. Rac1 Kf8
18. Qf5 $16 {[%csl Gf5] 1-0 Michiels,B (2546)-Nieto,E (2246)/Belgium BEL 2014/
The Week in Chess 1045 (31)}) 12. Qe2 Bxf3 ({Black is not in time to complete
his development comfortably} 12... Be7 13. d5 $36) 13. gxf3 Bd6 {1/2 Fraczek,D
(2376)-Dziuba,M (2562)/Krakow 2009/CBM 134 Extra (23)} {Here white would have
done much better with} 14. Nb5 $146 Bb8 15. d5 {and black would lose at least
a pawn after} O-O 16. dxe6 fxe6 17. Bxe6+ Kh8 18. f4 $16 {[%csl Rb8,Gf4]}) 11.
e4 {It was hard to find anything tangible in other lines:} (11. dxc5 {[%cal
Gd1d8] looks like the most logical continuation, but somehow black is getting
away even after losing another tempo:} Bxc5 {in 1/2 Onischuk,A (2678)
-Shankland,S (2512)/Saint Louis 2011/CBM 142 (30)} {Here white can improve on
the aforementioned game with} 12. Bb5 $5 {[%csl Rd7,Rd8,Re8][%cal Gb5e8,Gf3e5,
Gd1d8]} Qc7 13. Na4 $36 {[%csl Rc7,Rd7,Re8][%cal Gc2c7,Gb5e8] counting on a
minimal advantage in the endgame after} O-O 14. Nxc5 Qxc5 15. Qxc5 Nxc5 16. b3
Rfd8 17. Bb2 $14 {[%csl Gb2,Gb5] /=}) 11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 O-O (12... Qc7 $6 {
[%csl Rc7] was played in 1-0 (81) Brunello,S (2591)-De Filomeno,S (2356)
Torino ITA 2012, but it went unpunished.} 13. Ncb5 Qc8 14. Bf4 $1 {[%cal Gb5c7]
was the right continuation, when black gets into trouble:} Bxe4 15. Qe2 e5 16.
Rac1 $1 O-O 17. Bxf7+ Rxf7 18. Rxc8+ Rxc8 19. f3 $16) 13. Be3 {[%csl Rb7,Rd8]
[%cal Gf2f3] White goes for a small positional advantage described in 10...Qc8
11.Qe2 variation. Black also has some issues with his queen - it is not safe
on the d-file. Since there is no practical material in this line, I did some
analysis:} Bc5 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gd8e7]} (13... Ng4 $2 {would be very naive:}
14. Nxe6 Nxe3 15. fxe3 $18 {[%csl Rd7]}) (13... Qc8 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gd8c8]}
14. Be2 a6 15. f3 b5 16. a3 $14 {is a bit more pleasant for white. For example:
} Qc7 17. Qd2 Rac8 18. Rac1 Qb8 19. b4 Rfd8 20. Qe1 Ne5 21. Nb3 $14 {[%csl Ga5,
Ra6,Rb7,Gc5] such a small structural advantage can best be exploited in the
endgame, so white should have nothing against trading some pieces.}) 14. f3 Qe7
(14... Ne5 15. Be2 Nc6 16. Qd2 Bxd4 17. Bxd4 Nxd4 18. Qxd4 Qxd4+ 19. Rxd4 {
leads to a typical small advantage for white, who can use his spatial
advantage without any risk. For example} Rfd8 20. Rad1 Rxd4 21. Rxd4 Kf8 22.
Kf2 Ke7 23. Ke3 $14) 15. Qf2 Rac8 16. Be2 Rfd8 17. Rac1 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Ge4,Gf3]
The position is rich with play and white has an easier game.}) (8... Bd6 {does
not really belong here and white can immediately exploit it with} 9. e4 dxe4
10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Qc7 (11... Nf6 12. Bg5 $1 Qc7 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. c5 $14)
12. Be3 Nf6 13. c5 $1 {[%csl Rd6] This is one reason why bishop is better
placed on e7.} Be7 14. Bd3 Nd5 15. Bd2 h6 16. b4 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6] unable to
release his light-squared bishop with thematic c6-c5, black had to suffer in
passivity in 1-0 Sargissian,G (2685)-Sivuk,V (2467)/Rethymno 2012/CBM 149
Extra (58)}) 9. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Yd5c4,Yb3c4] The idea of this move is
primarily completing development with Bb2 and Rac1/d1. The option to retake on
c4 with the pawn in case of dxc4 is a bonus.} ({Given black's apparently
unassuming opening play, it seems logical to open up the center with} 9. e4
dxe4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 {However, things are not so simple and after} Nf6
12. Ne5 $1 Rc8 13. Rd1 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 O-O 15. Bf4 Ba8 $1 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 16. Rd3
c5 $132 {black got good counterplay in 1-0 Mamedyarov,S (2646)-Timofeev,A 
(2578)/Moscow 2004/CBM 100 (34)}) 9... O-O {Simply completing development,
though black can try to be more subtle with the following alternatives:} ({1)} 
9... dxc4 $5 10. bxc4 c5 {[%cal Gb7g2] This is a somewhat improved version of
the variation 8...dxc4 as black is one step closer to completing kingside
development. It has also become Dreev's favorite as of late.} 11. Qe2 {[%cal
Ge2f3] This move is not as principled as the pawn sacrifice 11.d5, but
unfortunately I was not able to find anything special there, while here we
have at least a rich middlegame.} O-O 12. Bb2 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gf3e5,Gf2f4]
Usually we see this kind of position with colors reversed in Queen's indian.
White should use his extra tempo to obtain initiative without delay. The
general plan is Rad1, Ne5 and f4 - with good attacking prospects. Below are
instructive examples:} cxd4 (12... Rc8 13. Rad1 Qc7 14. Nb5 Qb8 15. Ne5 Rfd8
16. f4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4f5]} Nf8 $6 17. f5 $40 {1-0 Agrest,E (2554)
