1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 {In this chapter we will
cover the sidelines after} 6. Qc2 {Besides 6...Bd6 (Chapters 4-10) and 6...b6 
(Chapter 2), black can also play:} a6 {which is reminiscent of the first
chapter (5...a6), but with a few important differences, which I will explain
in the comments to next move.} ({Besides this, black is left with several
options to develop his dark-squared bishop.   Firstly,} 6... Be7 7. b3 O-O 8.
Bd3 {usually just transposes into CHAPTER 2 after} b6) (6... Bb4 {is sometimes
played on a club level, but it is altogether unclear why black would put his
bishop there when white's queen is already defending the knight. White has
more than one way to reach advantageous positions, for example:} 7. a3 Ba5 {
the only logical continuation.} (7... Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 $14) 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Bc7
{[%cal Ge6e5]} 10. Bd2 dxc4 11. Bxc4 e5 12. Ba2 $14 {1-0 Lukacs,P (2435)
-Tischbierek,R (2425)/Polanica Zdroj 1986/EXT 1997 (33)  with a structure
similar to CHAPTER 6.}) ({Finally, black has an original way to develop the
bishop:} 6... g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] However, this is not such a good line for black
and may only serve as a surprise weapon. Still, our job is to discover the
proper way to play against it and here I would recommend a tricky idea:} 7. b3
Bg7 8. Ba3 $1 {Using the fact that e-pawn is on e6 so black cannot castle.} Bf8
({Harikrishna tried} 8... Ne4 {[%cal Gd8a5] 0-1 Czakon,J (2481)-Harikrishna,P 
(2684)/Benasque 2012/CBM 149 Extra (43)} {and here white should have played
simple chess:} 9. Bd3 Qa5 10. Bb2 f5 {[%csl Ge4]} 11. O-O O-O 12. Ne2 $14 {
[%csl Ra5,Rc8,Rg7][%cal Ge2f4,Gf3e5,Yf2f3] with a Stonewall pawn structure
where white has accomplished a lot and black a little.}) (8... c5 {can be
answered in the usual fashion (see CHAPTER 2)} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O
b6 {And white is again well-organized to play against the hanging pawns:} 12.
Na4 Ne4 13. Rac1 $36 {[%csl Rc5,Rg7] White has cleared the long diagonal,
rendering Bg7 useless. The bishop belongs to e7, to defend the c5 pawn.}) 9.
Bb2 Bg7 10. Be2 $1 {[%csl Gb2] The result of the bishop manoeuvre to a3 and
then back to b2 is that white has won an important tempo in the opening.} O-O
11. O-O Re8 {This was played in 1-0 Bukavshin,I (2539)-Utkin,V (2025)/St
Petersburg 2013/CBM 156 Extra, probably to avoid Ba3 attack in some lines and
also to support e6-e5.} ({Black could also try to fianchetto the other bishop
with} 11... b6 {but this is strongly met with the idea from CHAPTER 2:} 12. Ne5
$1 Nxe5 (12... Bb7 13. f4 Rc8 14. Bf3 $14) 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. f4 Bb7 (14... f6 {
is logical, to open up the bishop, but does not quite work:} 15. cxd5 $1 cxd5
16. Ba3 Re8 17. Nb5 $36 {[%csl Gb5,Gd6]}) 15. Ba3 Re8 16. Rad1 $36 {[%cal
Ge3e4,Gc4d5] White wants to take on d5 and open up with e3-e4. Black can try
to stop it with} f5 {but then white dominates anyhow with:} 17. cxd5 cxd5 18.
Nb5 $16 {[%csl Gd6]}) {Again, white should simply play} 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5
Nd7 14. f4 f6 (14... b6 15. Rad1 Bb7 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. e4 $16) 15. exf6 Nxf6 {
and here he has a beautiful knight manoeuvre:} 16. Nd1 $1 {[%csl Gf2][%cal
Gd1f2,Gb2g7]} b6 17. Nf2 Bb7 18. e4 $36) 7. b3 {[%cal Gb3c4] Compared to
CHAPTER 1, here black does not have Bb4 tempo as the knight is defended by
queen. On the other hand c6-c5 idea is not as effective because the knight can
not come to c6 any more. But black still wanted to take on c4 and push b5 with
tempo, thus 7.b3.} Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5] In given circumstances, this is the most
sensible plan. Black is using the fact that he already has a6, which makes it
easier to push e6-e5 without having to fear Nb5.} ({The alternatives are not
so consistent.} 7... b5 {[%cal Gc4c5] is the attempt to play actively on the
queenside, but always leaves black vulnerable to c4-c5.} 8. Bd3 (8. Be2 {is
also good, though I prefer Bd3. I provide the following games of strong
players primarily for instructive purposes:} Bd6 (8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Bb2
Bb7 11. Rad1 Rc8 12. c5 Qc7 13. b4 Ne8 14. Ne5 $1 Nxe5 15. dxe5 f6 (15... Qxe5
16. Nxd5) 16. Bg4 $1 {[%csl Re6]} f5 17. Be2 {[%csl Ge5]} a5 18. a3 g6 19. f4
$16 Ng7 20. Bd3 $1 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2d4]} Ra8 21. Ne2 a4 22. Nd4 Bc8 23. h3 {
[%csl Rg8][%cal Gg2g4]} Bd7 24. g4 h5 25. gxf5 exf5 26. Rd2 $1 Ne6 27. Rg2 {
[%csl Rg6]} Nxd4 28. Bxd4 Kh7 29. Kh1 Be6 30. Rfg1 Rg8 31. Rxg6 $1 {1-0
Tomashevsky,E (2540)-Popov,I (2476)/Nojabrsk 2005/CBM 106}) 9. O-O O-O 10. e4
dxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 Bb7 13. c5 $14 Be7 {[%csl Rb7]} 14. Bd3 Nf6 15. Qh4
Re8 16. Bg5 $1 h6 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Qe4 $16 {[%csl Ge4] Riazantsev,A (2692)
-Korobov,A (2680) Dubai UAE 2014}) 8... Bd6 ({If black plays} 8... Bb7 {
immediately, white should in principle close it down with} 9. c5 $1 {[%csl Rb7,
Rc6]} (9. O-O $6 {on the other hand, is what black hopes for} bxc4 10. bxc4
dxc4 11. Bxc4 c5 $11 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb7g2]}) 9... g6 10. O-O Bg7 11. e4 $1
dxe4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6,Gd6][%cal Gc1f4,Gf4d6] White
has obvious advantage. Square d6 is particularly inviting.} O-O 14. Bg5 Qe8 15.
