b5 $18 {and black was defenseless against the passed pawns...} Re4 36. Ra7 Rc8
37. Rd7 Rc4 38. Rxd5 Kh6 39. Kh2 f5 40. Kg3 Rc3 41. Kf3 f4 {1-0 Petrosian,T 
(2645)-Dorfman,J (2380)/Yerevan 1975/URS-ch}) (7... c5 {As I mentioned before,
it would be much better for black if he could follow up this move with Nc6
rather than Nbd7. Still, it is a decent plan that deserves our attention.} 8.
cxd5 exd5 9. Bb2 ({Here I would not recommend} 9. Bd3 {due to} b5 {[%cal Gc5c4]
}) 9... Be7 (9... b5 $2 {is a typical opening blunder} 10. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 11.
Qe4+ $18) 10. g3 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf1g2,Gg2d5] I already explained in the
CHAPTER 1 of the first volume of Repertoire against the Slav - the Classical
