Bb7 (12... Bd7 13. Bg2 {[%csl Rd5]}) 13. Bh3 $5 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rd5] preventing
Rc8, which is sometimes annoying to white queen.}) 8. Bb2 O-O ({If black goes
for} 8... e5 {immediately, then we get positions that are very similar to the
main line after:} 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bd3 Bd7 {[%cal
Ga8c8] the extra option that tries to save a tempo on 0-0.} ({Otherwise} 12...
O-O 13. Ne2 {is just a transposition into a position we will examine in the
main line 8...0-0 9.Bd3 e5.}) (12... d4 $6 {seems attractive in order to get
rid of the isolated pawn, but after} 13. exd4 Bxd4 14. O-O O-O 15. Rad1 {[%csl
Rd4][%cal Gd1d8] black can not get out of the pin comfortably} Bg4 16. Ne2 Rc8
17. Bc4 $1 $18 {and white wins the material.}) 13. Ne2 Rc8 (13... Qa5+ 14. Bc3
Bxc3+ 15. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 16. Nxc3 {transposes as well.}) 14. Qd2 Qe7 {1/2-1/2
Ramirez,A (2479)-Bhat,V (2429)/ICC INT 2005/CBM 108 Extra} {Here white could
simply play} 15. O-O O-O 16. Rac1 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5,Rd7][%cal Gc1c8] with the
IQP position that of course favors white. We will examine such positions
shortly.}) (8... Qe7 {is possible too, though it does not change anything
substantial.} 9. Bd3 e5 (9... dxc4 10. bxc4 e5 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4] is another type
of position where black avoids the isolani, but on the other hand gives white
central supremacy.} 11. O-O O-O 12. h3 Re8 13. Ng5 $1 h6 14. Nge4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4
{[%csl Ge4]} Bc7 16. Qb3 Nf6 17. Ba3 Qd8 18. d5 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd5d6]
1-0 Arencibia Rodriguez,W (2539)-Roussel Roozmon,T (2430)/Montreal 2006/CBM
113 Extra (32)}) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Ne2 {[%cal
Ge2d4,Gb2e5] The usual maneouvre.} Bg4 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 15. Nd4 Rc8 16. Qb2 O-O
17. O-O $14 {Let us see how to get more out of this pleasant, but tough to
break position:} Rc7 18. Rac1 Rfc8 19. h3 Bd7 20. Rxc7 Qxc7 21. Ne2 Qb6 22. Rc1
Rxc1+ 23. Qxc1 Qb4 24. Nd4 h6 25. a3 $1 {[%cal Gb3b4]} Qd6 26. b4 {[%csl Ga5,
Gc5]} Ne8 27. Nb3 Nc7 28. Na5 b6 29. Nb3 {[%csl Ra6,Rb6,Gc6]} Kf8 30. Qc3 Kg8
31. Nd4 Qe5 32. Be2 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Rb6,Gd4][%cal Gc3c8] 1-0 Mikhalevski,V 
(2598)-Lahaye,R (2367)/Ottawa 2007/CBM 119 Extra (101)}) 9. Bd3 {This is in
fact not the most popular move in this position. However, I do not see why it
would be any worse than the alternative 9.Be2. It is more active than Be2 and
it enables white to reach a favorable IQP endgame in case black proceeds with
his initial plan e6-e5.} (9. Be2 e5 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. O-O {is
the position preferred by strong white players, possibly because it leads to
more complex middlegame positions. However, after} Be6 ({or} 12... Bg4 {black
seems to be doing fine.})) 9... e5 {Going for the solid IQP position.} ({
Alternatively, black can continue} 9... Qe7 {but in such positions his a6 does
not make much sense.} 10. O-O dxc4 (10... e5 $6 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. e4 $1 $16 {
is the sequence we will investigate in a similar position in the next chapter.}
) ({I find} 10... Re8 $6 {to be inacurrate as well, on account of} 11. c5 $1
Bc7 12. e4 {a strong idea which we will also cover in one of the following
chapters.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Nf6 15. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Ge5]}) 11.
bxc4 e5 12. h3 h6 13. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gh4f5] f5 is a chronic weakness
for black in CHAPTER 6.} Bc7 14. Nf5 Qd8 15. Ba3 Re8 16. d5 $1 cxd5 17. Nxd5
Nxd5 18. cxd5 $16 {1-0 Kolev,A (2550)-Gil Gonzalez,J (2385)/Seville 1999/EXT
2000 (34)}) 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Rd5]
[%cal Gb2e5,Ge2d4] That is why I prefer to put the bishop to d3 in this line.
All white pieces work harmoniously.} Qa5+ {This move forces queen exchange. In
general black should avoid exchanges in IQP positions, but here he can not
avoid exchange of his dark-squared bishop, without which there is no attack.
After trading queens black hopes to create a super-solid position by putting a
rook on the c-file, king on d6, and knight on e6. Many of such endgames indeed
finish in a draw, so if he wants to win, white needs to know something more
than just the fact that this position is better for him.} (13... Bxb2 14. Qxb2
Bg4 {was an attempt to keep the queens on board.} 15. Nd4 Qd6 16. O-O Rac8 17.
Rfc1 Rfd8 18. Rxc8 Rxc8 19. Rc1 Rc7 20. h3 Bd7 21. Rc3 g6 22. b4 $14 {[%csl
Ra6,Rb7][%cal Gd4b3,Gb3c5] 1/2-1/2 Doettling,F (2473)-Gurevich,M (2667)/
Germany 2000/CBM 082 Extra (54) Obviously this is very pleasant for white. He
prepares Nb3-c5/a5 and starts harrasing black on the queenside.}) 14. Bc3 Bxc3+
15. Qxc3 Qxc3+ ({After} 15... Qa3 16. b4 Qxc3+ 17. Nxc3 a5 $5 18. b5 {we get a
slightly different pawn structure, but the position remains difficult for
black.} Be6 19. Ne2 Rfc8 20. f3 {[%csl Ge4,Gg4]} Nd7 21. Kd2 {[%csl Gd2]} Nb6
22. Nd4 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Re6][%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4,Ga1c1] 1/2 (51) Popov,V (2588)
-Tkachiev,V (2609) Moscow 2005 (51)  The bishop is a spectator on e6 and white
has many ways to improve his position. Weakness of c4 square is not of great
importance.}) 16. Nxc3 Bd7 {Correct, as e6 square should be reserved for the
knight.} (16... Be6 {[%csl Re6] is less precise.} 17. Rc1 Rfd8 18. Ne2 Rac8 19.
Rxc8 Rxc8 20. f3 Kf8 21. Kd2 Ke7 22. g4 $1 {Gaining space on the kingside to
provoke weaknesses later on.} Nd7 23. Nd4 Ne5 24. h4 g6 25. Rb1 $1 {[%cal
Gb3b4] White switches his focus to the queenside now.} Kd6 26. a4 Nc6 27. Nxc6
Rxc6 28. b4 Rc8 29. a5 $14 {[%csl Gd3,Re6][%cal Gb4b5,Gg4g5] and white
dominated the whole board in 1-0 Jakubowski,K (2565)-Ali Marandi,C (2431)/
Pardubice 2015/CBM 167 Extra (46)}) 17. f3 Rfc8 18. Kd2 h5 $1 {A good
prophylactic move. White would have liked to expand with g2-g4 etc.} 19. Ne2
Kf8 {This position was reached in a high-profile game Leko-Ni Hua. After
analyzing the game, I came to conclusion that white should have played} 20. b4
$1 $146 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] The idea is to fix black's pawn
structure on light-squares with a4-a5.} ({In the game, Leko played less
concrete moves and allowed black to slowly equalize.} 20. Nd4 {The knight
looks great here, but it does not have much to do.} Ke7 21. g3 g6 22. h3 Ne8 $1
{[%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6]} 23. Ne2 Nc7 24. Nf4 Kd6 25. g4 Rh8 $1 26. Rad1 (26. gxh5
g5 $1) 26... a5 $1 $132 27. Ke2 a4 28. b4 hxg4 29. hxg4 a3 $11 {1/2-1/2 Leko,P
(2728)-Ni,H (2670)/Saratov 2011/CBM 145}) 20... Ke7 ({Black can block the pawn
with} 20... Ba4 {but this is only temporary:} 21. Nc3 $1 Bd7 22. a4 {and if} a5
{then} 23. Rhb1 $1 axb4 24. Rxb4 Bc6 25. a5 $36 {[%csl Rb7]}) 21. a4 g6 22. a5
{[%csl Ra6,Rb7] It is important to note that the isolated pawn is often the
least of black's concerns in such positions. Since it is well-defended, white
will usually play around it for a long time until he creates a weakness on the
other side of the board. The Russian chess school refers to this effective
strategy as "a principle of two weaknesses".} Ne8 {[%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6]} 23. Nf4
{[%csl Gf4] This is the best square for the knight, not d4.} Nc7 24. Rac1 Bc6
25. h4 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7,Rc6,Rd5,Rf7,Rg6,Rh5] Black's pawn structure is funny.
Especially the one on c6. Still, he is very solid.} Ne6 26. Nxe6 Kxe6 27. g4 $1
$14 {White finally found a weakness. He will either get a passed pawn on the
h-file (in case black takes on g4) or fix black kingside with g5 (after Rh8).
Either way, black is in for a long and unpleasant journey.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "Ekaterinburg"]
[Date "2016.03.04"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Semi-Slav"]
[Black "CHAPTER 4: 8...e5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D46"]
[Annotator "GM Kuljasevic, Davorin"]
[PlyCount "95"]
[EventDate "2006.03.11"]
[SourceDate "2016.01.25"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 {[%cal Ge8g8]
This is the main move, aiming to complete kingside development. White has many
options here: 7.Bd3, 7.b3, 7.Be2, 7.Bd2, and even the crazy Shirov-Shabalov
gambit 7.g4!? I have played the Anti-Meran for white for 15 years now and have
tried all of these moves. There are pluses and minuses to all of them, so it
is difficult to determine which one is the best in trivial terms. However, I
do have a small inclination towards -} 7. Bd3 {[%csl Gd3,Rh7][%cal Gc2h7,Re3e4]
At this opening stage, d3 seems to be the most natural square for the bishop
as we have the battery of queen and bishop on b1-h7 diagonal. It also supports
the thematic e3-e4 push, which prevents black from playing b7-b6 comfortably.
The drawback is that black can now take on c4 with a tempo. As I said, there
are two sides to the coin for each variation on white's move 7.} (7. b3 {[%cal
Gb3c4]}) (7. Be2 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Ge3e4]}) (7. Bd2) (7. g4 $5) 7... O-O 8. O-O
e5 {This is the most direct attempt to equalize the game in the Anti-Meran.
Quite a few top players have used it succesfully (meaning achieved a draw),
but the downside is that black's winning chances are practically non-existent.
Therefore, it is not nearly as popular as 8...dxc4, but nevertheless white
needs to know how to get the most out of these relatively dry positions:} 9.
cxd5 cxd5 {Black is going for the IQP position after the exchange on e5, where
Bd3 is not placed so well as on e2.} 10. e4 $1 {However, white strikes back in
the center. The battery Qc2-Bd3 will be very important once the center clears
up because h7 pawn will be hanging.} exd4 ({The alternative is} 10... dxe4 11.
Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Bxe4 {[%cal Gc2h7] Black is now forced to waste a valuable tempo
on} h6 13. Be3 exd4 ({the inclusion of} 13... Re8 14. Rad1 {is even better for
white:} exd4 15. Bh7+ Kh8 16. Bxd4 $16 {1-0 Ribli,Z (2585)-Dobosz,H (2433)/
Austria 2005/EXT 2006 (58)}) 14. Bh7+ $1 {An important intermediate check with
the idea to force black king into a worse position on h8. This will work into
white's favor for tactical reasons, as we will see in a bit. Another benefit
is that the king is placed worse on h8 than g8 for the endgame.} Kh8 {[%csl
Rh8]} 15. Bxd4 Nf6 16. Bf5 {[%csl Gc2,Gd4,Gf5,Rh8] White has a nagging
pressure thanks to more active pieces and better development.} Qa5 {This is
more active} ({than} 16... Bxf5 17. Qxf5 $14 {[%csl Gd4,Gf5]} Qc8 {The
powerful queen ought to be exchanged.} (17... Qd7 $6 {fails tactically to} 18.
Qxd7 Nxd7 19. Rfd1 {[%csl Rd6,Rd7][%cal Gd4a7,Gd4g7]} Rfd8 20. Bxa7 $16) {This
was the game between Karpov and Kramnik from 1996. It is one of those games
one must see as a part of general chess education:} 18. Qb5 (18. Qxc8 Raxc8 19.
Bxf6 gxf6 20. Rad1 Rfd8 $14 {Karpov}) 18... a6 19. Qb6 $1 (19. Qb3 Qe6 20. Qxe6
fxe6 21. Rfe1 Rfe8 $14 {Karpov}) 19... Qc7 20. Qxc7 Bxc7 21. Bxf6 gxf6 $14 {
[%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rh6] This pawn structure does not promise anything good to black
in the endgame. Let's see how Karpov proceeded to take advantage of it.} 22.
Rfe1 Rfe8 23. Rad1 Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 Rd8 25. g3 Rd7 26. Re2 Kg7 27. Nh4 {[%csl
Gf5][%cal Gh4f5]} Rd5 {Kramnik did not want to allow Karpov to bring his
knight to f5, but on the other hand, he let his rook penetrate the 7th rank.}
28. Re7 {[%csl Ge7]} Rc5 29. Rd7 b5 30. b4 {[%csl Ra6] The idea of this move
is to fix black pawns and create the first target on a6.} Rc2 31. Nf5+ Kg6 32.
Ne3 Rc1+ 33. Kg2 Be5 34. Ra7 {[%csl Ra6] The first part of the plan is
completed. The second part is to create another weakness on the other side of
the board.} Rc6 35. Nd5 Bd6 36. a3 Kf5 37. Ne3+ Kg6 38. Kf3 (38. f4 $5 $16 {
[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd6c5,Gd6e5] was good, too, to restrict the movement of black
bishop.}) 38... Be5 39. Nd5 Kg7 40. Ne7 $1 {Karpov sacrifices a pawn for
kingside attack!} Rc3+ 41. Kg4 Rxa3 42. f4 Bc3 43. Kh5 $1 {[%csl Rg6,Gh5][%cal
Ge7f5] Karpov proves time and again that king is such a strong piece in the
endgame.} Bxb4 44. Nf5+ Kg8 45. Ra8+ Kh7 46. Ra7 Kg8 47. Nxh6+ Kf8 48. Rxf7+
Ke8 {and now all white has to do is clear the way for the passed h-pawn:} 49.
