plan that deserves attention is} 24. g3 {[%cal Gg1g2,Gg2f3]} a6 25. Rd3 $1 {
[%cal Gd3b3]} Rd8 26. Rb3 b5 27. Ra3 {White is looking to provoke queenside
weaknesses he would attack later on.} a5 28. Rc3 $1 {[%cal Gc3c6,Gc6a6] Now he
switches to attack from the back.} Nd5 29. Rc6 Rd7 (29... Nxe3 30. fxe3 Rd7 31.
Kf2 g6 32. Ke2 Kg7 33. Nd4 $14 {[%csl Ra5,Rb5]}) 30. Bc5 Kg8 31. Kg2 $14) 24...
a6 25. h3 Kg8 26. b3 {The last two white moves were by no means forced.} Rd8
27. Rxd8+ Bxd8 {It seems like black has solved his problems, but white will
have initiative even in endgame of light pieces thanks to better position of
his king.} 28. Ke2 {[%csl Ge2]} h5 $6 {A mistake in judgement by the ex-world
champion.} (28... Nd5 {was better} 29. Bd2 Kf8 30. Kd3 Ke7 31. Nd4 Kd7 32. Kc4
$14 {[%csl Gc4]}) 29. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gg5d8]} Kf8 30. Kd3 Ke8 31. Bxf6
Bxf6 32. Ke4 $36 {Anand probably thought that bishop would have no problems
against the knight in this type of endgame, but he was wrong. White will bring
