1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 {Gelfand,B: 'Winants: 'La défense
demi-slave ; le triangle b7-d5-f7 indique l'intention des Noirs de jouer
autour du pion d4, sur les cases blanches, mais présente aussi l'invénient de
laisser le Fc8 enfermé. C'est pourquoi les Blancs devront bientôt tenir compte
du coup libérateur e6-e5 ou de l'échange sur c4 et du fianchetto en b7, aprčs
b7-b5.''} 5. e3 {Gelfand,B: 'Winants: 'Un coup tranquille oů les Blancs ne
forment d'autre projet immédiat que d'achever leur développement sans encombre.
''} Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O {We have already seen in CHAPTER 4 a
direct attempt to open the center with 8...e5. Before we move on to the main
line 8...dxc4, we need to take a look at some alternatives that black can
throw your way. The most notable one is} h6 {[%csl Gh6,Rh7] which is a
prophylactic move against white's e3-e4.} ({We can see why black play h6
before b6 here:} 8... b6 $6 9. e4 dxe4 (9... dxc4 {is probably objectively
better, though it can lead to a position where black is a tempo down compared
to the normal line after} 10. Bxc4 e5 11. h3 $5 $146 b5 12. Bd3 Bb7 13. dxe5
Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Be3 $14 {this is a regular position from one of the
variations that could arise after 8...dxc4 9.Bxc4 b5 10.Bd3. There black has
an extra tempo a6, which enables him to equalize with a temporary pawn
sacrifice c6-c5! Here however, he does not have that possiblity, which of
course changes the evaluation of the position.}) 10. Nxe4 Bc7 (10... Be7 {is
even worse:} 11. Bf4 {[%csl Gd6]} Bb7 12. Nd6 $16) 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 Bb7 13.
Rad1 Qe7 14. Ne5 $1 $36 Nxe5 15. Nxf6+ gxf6 16. dxe5 Bxe5 17. Qe2 $40 {1-0
Markos,J (2178)-Motuz,K (2275)/Slovakia 1999/EXT 2001 (30)}) ({A common
apparently useful move is} 8... Qe7 {but white can use the position of the
queen to his advantage with} 9. c5 $1 Bc7 10. e4 dxe4 {black is forced to give
up the control of center} ({since} 10... e5 11. exd5 cxd5 {runs into} 12. Re1
$1 {[%cal Ge1e7]} e4 13. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 14. Bxe4 $18 {[%csl Re7] and in the end
black is losing precisely because of unfortunate position of his queen.}) 11.
Nxe4 $14 {[%csl Gc5,Rc8,Gd4,Re6] this kind of pawn structure is generally
favorable for white if two conditions are met: 1.black can not free himself
with e6-e5 and 2.black can not trade his light-squared bishop. With good piece
coordination white can count on even more than a minimal advantage in the long
run, as black will soon run out of good moves in such a cramped position.} Nxe4
({It is important to note why} 11... e5 $2 {doesn't work now:} 12. Nxf6+ Nxf6 (
12... Qxf6 13. Bxh7+ $18) 13. dxe5 {And black loses a pawn again because of
bad position of his queen.} Bxe5 14. Re1 $18) (11... h6 12. Re1 Rd8 {1/2-1/2
Dautov,R (2615)-Shirov,A (2685)/Germany 1996/GER-chT/[Dautov] (26)} ({Here if} 
12... Nxe4 {white has an additional attacking option in} 13. Rxe4 $1 Nf6 14.
Rh4 $40 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gh4h6] with some sacrificial ideas. For example:} Nd5
15. Bg5 f6 16. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 17. Rg4+ Kh8 18. Qd2 Bf4 19. Rxf4 Nxf4 20. Qxf4 Qg7
21. Re1 $16 {[%csl Rg6,Rh6][%cal Gf3h4,Ge1e3]}) 13. Bd2 $14 {with advantage
similar to the main line.}) (11... Nd5 12. Bd2 Rd8 13. Rae1 {Le Fc8 reste
enfermé derričre ses lignes} f6 14. Nd6 $1 {[%cal Gd3h7] aiming to exchange
the key defender of e6 pawn.} Nf8 15. Nxc8 Raxc8 16. Re4 {[%csl Re6]} Qf7 17.
Rfe1 Re8 18. b4 a6 19. a4 Ra8 20. g3 Qd7 21. Bc4 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Re6] not a
