Qh4 17. g3 Qh5 18. Be4 $16 {and white consolidated his material advantage. The
following aggresive attempt was punished convincingly by Bacrot:} f5 19. f4 $1
fxe4 20. fxe5 Bh3 21. exd6 Bxf1 22. Rxf1 Rxf1+ 23. Kxf1 Qxd5 24. d7 Rf8+ 25.
Kg1 Qf7 26. Qe2 Qxd7 27. Qxe4 $18 {with a technically winning position in 1-0
Bacrot,E (2712)-Di Nicolantonio,L (2371)/Deizisau 2015/CBM 165 Extra (50)}) {
Such a long hesitation by black should be a sign for white to create the
good-old bind:} 11. c5 Bc7 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 $14 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 e5 {[%csl
Ra8,Gb2,Rc8,Rd7,Ge4][%cal Gf1e1] This would be the point of all the previous
black moves. However, being fully developed, white can afford to allow black
to play this move. In fact, he can turn it to his advantage by using the open
e-file:} 15. Rac1 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1c5]} exd4 16. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge1e8]} Qd8
{1/2-1/2 Farago,I (2467)-Trabert,B (2273)/Bolzano 2000/CBM 077 Extra (18)} {
and here white should have inserted the well-known useful check} 17. Bh7+ $1
$146 Kh8 18. Bxd4 Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Nf8 20. Be4 $36 {[%csl Gc2,Rc7,Rc8,Gd4,Ge1,
Ge4,Rh8] and white has excellent attacking prospects with these bishops.}) 10.
Bb2 Bb7 {[%csl Ga1,Gf1][%cal Gd8c7,Gd8e7] If this position looks familiar, it
is because we saw the same setup in CHAPTER 2, only with black bishop on e7
rather than on d6. The main difference is that black queen is more flexible in
this case as it can also go to e7, not only to c7 as in CHAPTER 2. If you
remember, there we recommended to put the rooks on c1 and d1 in order to
target the queen on c7 and force it to retreat to b8. Here, however, we need
to be more flexible as queen is indeed placed well on e7. Therefore, I suggest}
11. Rad1 {[%cal Gf1e1,Gd8e7,Ge1e7] which is aimed against Qe7.} Qc7 {[%csl Gc7,
Gd1] This is the principled answer now that this rook has foregone a chance to
come to c1 (assuming white does not want to waste an important tempo on that).}
({Should black play} 11... Qe7 {anyway, white has a strong retort:} 12. Rfe1 {
[%cal Ge1e7]} Rac8 (12... Rfd8 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Nf6 16. Bd3
$14 {[%csl Ge1,Re7][%cal Rc6c5,Gd4d5] is pleasant for white as the freeing
c6-c5 runs into d4-d5.} Bb4 17. Re3 Ba3 18. Ba1 $1 Ng4 19. Re2 Bd6 20. Qc3 Bb4
21. Qc1 Qc7 22. Bb1 $1 {white developed attack in a very instructive way:} Be7
23. Qc2 Nf6 24. Ne5 Bd6 25. Rde1 $40 {1-0 Dreev,A (2655)-Przybylski,W (2326)/
Warsaw 2009/CBM 133 Extra (38)}) 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Nf6 16. Bd3
Rfd8 17. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Gb2,Rb7,Gd3,Ge5,Re7] with a classical advantage for
white.} Qf8 {[%csl Gf8]} 18. Qe2 Bb4 (18... c5 {was better} 19. dxc5 Bxc5 20.
Bc3 $14) 19. Rf1 Ba3 20. Ba1 Rc7 21. Bb1 $1 Be7 22. Qc2 $40 g6 23. Rfe1 Ne8 24.
d5 $1 $18 {1-0 Arlandi,E-Ortega,L/ITA 1998/EXT 99 (60)}) (11... Rc8 {is an
interesting flexible move. Black wants to play c6-c5 without defining the
position of his queen just yet. White should play} 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4
14. Bxe4 Nf6 15. Bd3 c5 {and now strong is} 16. d5 $1 exd5 17. cxd5 a6 {1/2-1/
2 Prakash,G (2435)-Sandipan,C (2424)/Guntur 2000/CBM 077 (61)} (17... Nxd5 $2
18. Bh7+ Kh8 19. Be4) {Here white missed a relatively simple way to launch the
