kingside that my late coach used to call - "old man's teeth".}) 16. g3 c5 {
black managed to play c5, but to no avail.} 17. d5 $1 exd5 18. cxd5 {[%csl Gb2,
Gd5]} Ne5 19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Nh4 $1 $40 {[%csl Gf5,Rg7]} Be7 $2 21. Rfe1 Ng4 22.
Rxe7 $1 Qxe7 23. Bxg7+ Kxg7 24. Nf5+ {A very nice attacking game: 1-0
Svetushkin,D (2576)-Moen,A (2333)/Rethymnon 2011/CBM 143 Extra}) ({Another
typical way to prepare c6-c5 is} 14... f5 15. Bd3 c5 {but here, too, white can
close down the bishop with} 16. d5 Nf6 ({and the pawn is untouchable} 16...
exd5 17. cxd5 Bxd5 $2 {due to} 18. Bc4 {[%csl Rg8]} Bxc4 19. Qxc4+ Rf7 20. Qd5
$18 {[%cal Gd5d6,Gd5a8]}) 17. Rfe1 Rae8 18. dxe6 Ne4 19. Bxe4 fxe4 {[%csl Gb7,
Ge4]} 20. Rxe4 $1 {That is a great example of a positional exchange sacrifice.}
Bxe4 21. Qxe4 $16 {[%csl Gb2,Ge6] 1-0 Swapnil,S (2409)-Lock,G (2182)/Hastings
2011/CBM 140 Extra (58)}) ({A very interesting attempt by GM Lautier was} 14...
Be7 $5 {where black was patiently waiting for the right moment to push c5,
rather than forcing the issue as in previous examples.} 15. Rfe1 ({Of course,
