1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O
dxc4 9. Bxc4 e5 {We have already seen a variation of the e6-e5 plan in CHAPTER
4. The difference is that here black takes on c4 first, which gives the
position some new features. The most important one is that it is not so easy
for white to push e3-e4, so the game remains static for a while. Objectively
speaking, this line is reliable for black and I am a little surprised that
only a handful of strong players (Ponomariov, Akopian, Matlakov are the most
prominent ones) have used it more than once or twice.} {There are many
possible roads for white from this point. Some people, like Karpov, like to
play with 10.a3 and Ba2; others prefer 10.Rd1; while there are also 10.Bd2 and
10.Bb3. Very often people combine these developing moves, so we get different
move orders that transpose to same or similar positions. So, just as the
previous sentence, the theory of this line can be quite confusing, especially
for someone who is just learning it. I have, therefore, tried to keep it
straightforward and relatively simple to understand and memorize.} 10. h3 {
[%csl Gg4][%cal Rf6g4,Re5e4] This prophylactic move prevents all sorts of
tactics related to a potentially vulnerable h2 square. It is also useful to
take g4 square under control.   Let us now talk about black's plans. Ideally,
he would like to play either Qe7 or Re8 to push e5-e4, which can be quite
unpleasant if black also manages to throw in Nb6 tempo followed by Bf5.
Black's general strategic idea is summarized well in the game Gustafsson -
Ponomariov below.} (10. Bb3 h6 11. h3 Re8 {[%cal Ge5e4]} 12. Bd2 e4 13. Nh4 Bb8
$1 {[%cal Gd8c7]} 14. Nf5 Nb6 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 15. Ng3 {[%csl Re4]} Bxg3 $1 16.
fxg3 Be6 $11 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4] 0-1 Gustafsson,J (2629)-Ponomariov,R (2726)/
Dortmund 2012/CBM 150 (70)}) 10... h6 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gf8e8,Rf3g5] This is a
relatively new idea, popularized by Ponomariov. Black prepares Re8 instead of
Qe7 and also prevents Bg5 in lines where he takes exd4.} ({The old main line is
} 10... Qe7 {which also leads to reasonable positions for black.} 11. Bb3 {
Removing the bishop from Nb6 tempo. White should not fear 11...e4 since he has
12.Ng5, targeting both e4 and f7, so he wins a pawn. Had he not played 11.Bb3,
black could defend the central pawn with 11...Nb6 12.Bb3 and Bf5. The devil is
in the detail!} Bc7 {Black plays this prophylactic move to avoid a tempo on
the bishop after Nh4-f5. This part of the game is quite slow and deliberate -
both sides are trying to carefully prepare their forces before the position
inevitably opens up.} ({We can understand why black usually play Bc7 before h6
from the following line:} 11... h6 12. Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4f5,Gh4g6] A double
threat Ng6-Nf5 doesn't give black much choice.} Re8 (12... Rd8 13. Nf5 Qf8 14.
Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Rd1 $14 {yielded white a nice advantage of two bishops.} Re8 16.
Qg6 Qe7 17. e4 $1 {[%cal Gc1h6]} Nf8 18. Qg3 exd4 19. Rxd4 $16 {1-0 Barsov,A 
(2465)-Strating,S (2275)/Wijk aan Zee 1998/EXT 2002 (47)}) 13. Nf5 Qf8 14. Bd2
({White can also take the bishop immediately} 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 {though after} 15.
Rd1 e4 {[%csl Ge4] things are getting a bit complex and I promised to keep it
simple.}) {Probably the best for black here is to play} 14... Bc7 {transposing
to the line 11...Bc7 anyway.} ({Otherwise after} 14... Nb6 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16.
dxe5 Qxe5 17. e4 $14 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf2f4] white gets exactly what he wants
in the Meran - a potential for a strong pawn majority on the kingside.} Nxe4 $4
18. Nxe4 Qxe4 19. Rae1 {1-0 Voltolini,G (2260)-Villa,F/Porto San Giorgio 1999/
EXT 2000})) ({An even more sophisticated version of Bc7 is} 11... Bb8 {Other
than stopping Nb5 in certain lines, the points behind this move are too subtle
for me. Let's just say that the game goes on similarly to 11...Bc7 variation.}
12. Bd2 h6 13. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4g6,Gh4f5]} Rd8 14. Nf5 Qf8 ({Practically, the
only independent try compared to 11...Bc7 is} 14... Qe8 {With bishop on c7,
white would win with Nb5, but here this is not an option. However, white has
another strong resource using vulnerable position of black queen.} 15. f4 $1
$36 {[%csl Re5,Re8]} exd4 (15... e4 {loses the pawn to} 16. Ng3) 16. exd4 {
[%cal Ga1e1,Ge1e8]} Qf8 {So black needs to play Qf8 anyway.} (16... Nf8 17.
Rae1 Be6 {would seem tenable for black, but white has a powerful pawn break,
quite thematic in IQP positions.} 18. d5 $3 {[%csl Re6] closing down the
bishop on e6 so that he can not take on b3 any more.} Nxd5 (18... cxd5 19.
Nxh6+ $1 gxh6 20. f5 Kg7 21. fxe6 fxe6 22. Rxf6 $1 $40 Kxf6 23. Bxh6 Qh5 24.
Qf2+ Kg6 25. Rxe6+ $1 $18 {black was brutally checkmated in 1-0 Shariyazdanov,
A-Sasikiran,K/Guntur, AP 2000/CBM 77/[Lutz] (32)}) 19. Nxd5 cxd5 20. Nxh6+ $1
$18 gxh6 21. f5 $18 {[%csl Re6,Rg8] Black position is in ruins. This was first
played in 1-0 Wojtkiewicz,A (2567)-Orzechowski,J (2293)/Suwalki 1999/EXT 2000
and then later repeated in 1-0 Karpov,A (2699)-Gurevich,M (2667)/Cap d'Agde
2000/CBM 080/[Lutz,C] (26)}) {White has several ways to strengthen his
position - a positional one is} 17. Rae1 Nb6 18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Nxc8 Rxc8 20. Ne4
$14 {[%csl Gb3,Ge4] 1-0 Tratar,M (2410)-Polajzer,D (2416)/Bled 2000/EXT 2001 
(26)}) 15. Rad1 Nb6 16. Rfe1 {[%csl Rb8] we reach the position from the main
line of 11...Bc7, only with black bishop on b8. As you refer to the main line,
I let you conclude who benefits more from this difference.}) ({We complete the
list of sound moves with} 11... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb7a6] However reasonable,
this move is a bit out of place as black's premise in 9...e5 is to develop the
light-squared bishop somewhere along the diagonal c8-h3. This developing
scheme also does not support black's idea to push e5-e4 and white can use this
opportunity to push e4 himself:} 12. Rd1 $1 {[%cal Ge3e4,Yd1d4] If white wants
to play e3-e4, he needs to make sure that d4 square is well-supported.} Ba6 (
12... Bb7 13. e4 exd4 (13... Rad8 14. Bg5 $36 {[%csl Gb3,Gd4,Ge4,Gg5] is very
nice for white and if black is not careful enough} h6 $2 15. Nh4 $1 $18 {[%csl
Rd6,Re7,Gf5][%cal Gh4f5] he may even resign early.}) (13... c5 $6 {lead to a
