We will see more of that in the following chapters.} g6 15. Bg5 $16 Bb4 $2 16.
a3 Bxc3 17. Qxc3 c5 18. Nf3 $18 {[%csl Re7,Rf6][%cal Gd1d7,Ge4e5] and black
position quickly fell apart in 1-0 Rodshtein,M (2632)-Kozenkov,V (2132)/St
Petersburg 2010/EXT 2011 (25)}) 13. e4 {[%csl Gb3,Gd4,Ge4][%cal Gc1g5] The
structure resembles more to the one we see in chapters 7 to 10. This is a very
good version for white.} Rac8 (13... Rfd8 {[%csl Rf7]} 14. Ng5 $1 Rf8 15. dxe5
Nxe5 16. f4 $36 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] That's what white was hoping for.} Ng6 17. e5
Bc5+ 18. Kh2 $18 {1-0 Pulvett,D (2423)-Vidal Melendez,I (2300)/Lecheria 2014/
CBM 158 Extra (31)}) 14. Bg5 Rfe8 {1/2 (17) Portisch,L (2630)-Beliavsky,A 
(2665) Budapest 1997} {and now white had a simple and strong maneuvre} 15. dxe5
Nxe5 16. Nd4 $16 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gd4f5]}) ({Now that we have covered the most
reasonable moves in this position, let us take a quick look at the more
dubious ones:} 11... Nb6 $6 12. dxe5 Bxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. e4 $16 {[%csl Gb3,
Gc1][%cal Gc1e3,Gf2f4] 1-0 Karpov,A (2674)-Kubista,D (1987)/Vienna 2005/EXT
2007 (37)}) (11... exd4 $6 12. exd4 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ge1e7]} Nb6 13. Re1 Qc7
14. Bg5 $36 {black basically lost a full tempo compared to 10...h6 11.Bb3 exd4
line in 1-0 (33) Karpov,A (2690)-Kosteniuk,A (2459) Manises 2002}) (11... g6 $6
{was original try by young Fedoseev, but also not very succesful.} 12. e4 {
[%cal Gc1g5]} exd4 13. Nxd4 Re8 14. Bg5 $36 Be5 15. Nf3 Nc5 16. Rfe1 Nxb3 17.
axb3 Qc7 18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. Qd2 Be6 20. b4 $16 {[%csl Rg8] 1/2 (38)
Khismatullin,D (2654)-Fedoseev,V (2477) St Petersburg 2010}) ({On} 11... c5 $6
