1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O
dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 {[%cal Gc6c5,Rb7b5] This flexible move has been introduced
into practice by Hungarian theoreticians GMs Ribli and Lukacs, mostly with the
idea to follow it up with c6-c5. It was soon picked up by Anand who brought
some new ideas related to a more ambitious push b7-b5.} {White has quite a few
possibilities from this position. The one I would recommend is} 10. Rd1 {[%cal
Rc6c5,Re6e5] The rook is generally useful on the d-file as it makes it more
difficult for black to execute one of his thematic pawn breaks.} ({For a while,
people thought b7-b5 should be stopped with} 10. a4 {but it was proved that
black obtains good chances to equalize with} c5) 10... b5 {This is the most
straightforward approach. Black has several alternatives as well.} ({As I
already mentioned,} 10... c5 {is a decent try to balance the pawn structure
and equalize the game.} 11. dxc5 {[%cal Gd1d8]} Bxc5 {Now we get a QGA-like
position.} 12. Bd3 $1 {This is the move that gives black the most difficulties
completing his queenside development. The point is that b5 is not a tempo any
more and also Nc3-e4 becomes unpleasant for black, as we will see.} Qe7 {
Removing the queen from d-file before pushing the b-pawn makes sense.} ({Also
in the case of} 12... b5 13. Ne4 $1 {black needs to move his queen -} Qe7 (
13... Nxe4 $2 {loses a pawn} 14. Bxe4 {[%cal Ge4h7,Ge4a8]}) 14. Bd2 Bb7 ({
Saving the dark-squared bishop} 14... Bb6 {comes at a cost of important tempo}
15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 16. a3 $1 {[%cal Gd2b4] a familiar motive from CHAPTER 6} Rd8
17. Bb4 Qe8 18. Bc3 $36 {with obvious initiative for white. For example:} h6
19. a4 $1 bxa4 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Rxa4 $40 {[%cal Ga4h4]}) 15. Nxc5 Qxc5 16.
Qxc5 Nxc5 17. Be2 $14 {[%cal Gd2b4,Gb4a5] with a position very similar to the
main line. The presence of pawn on b5 (compared to b6 in the main line) makes
the scope of white's dark-squared bishop even greater.}) ({A popular way for
black to defend against Ne4 idea is to play} 12... h6 {[%csl Gh6,Rh7]
immediately. The game transposes to the main line anyway after:} 13. Bd2 b6 14.
Ne4 Bb7 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. Be2 {-12..Qe7}) ({The queen is not placed so well on
c7 as on e7:} 12... Qc7 13. Bd2 b6 {Black are usually more restrained with
this pawn for a good reason} ({Since} 13... b5 {is often attacked with} 14. a4
$1 {[%csl Rb5]} bxa4 15. Nxa4 Bd6 16. Qxc7 Bxc7 17. Bb4 Re8 18. Rac1 $16 {
[%csl Ga4,Ra8,Gb4,Gc1,Rc7,Rc8,Gd1,Re8] with a huge initiative for white.}) 14.
Ne4 Bb7 15. Nxc5 Qxc5 16. Qxc5 Nxc5 17. Be2 $14 {[%csl Gd2,Ge2] Finally we
reached a position similar to the main line, only without the queens on the
board which, of course, favors white.} Rfd8 18. Ne5 Nfe4 19. Be1 b5 20. f3 $1 {
[%csl Ge4]} f6 21. Ng4 Ng5 22. Bb4 Na4 23. b3 Nb6 24. e4 $16 {[%csl Gb4,Rb7,
Ge4,Gf3,Gg2] with a strategically winning position in 1-0 (52) Bocharov,D 
(2611)-Pakhomov,E (2396) Tomsk 2012}) (12... Be7 $6 {is too cautious and
allows white to play} 13. e4 $1 {[%cal Ge4e5] (This move would not be possible
with bishop on c5 due to Ng4)} Qc7 14. Bg5 Ne5 15. Nd5 $1 {An excellent
tactical shot - leading into a much better endgame:} Nxd5 16. Qxc7 Nxc7 17.
Bxe7 Re8 18. Nxe5 Rxe7 19. Rac1 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Gc1,Rc7,Rc8,Gd1,Ge5] 1-0 (32)
Pashikian,A (2618)-Froewis,G (2407) Plovdiv 2012 CBM 148}) 13. Bd2 {[%cal
Ga1c1,Gc3e4] Quick development is of paramount importance for white if he
wants to keep the initiative going in this symmetrical pawn structure.} h6 14.
Rac1 b6 15. Ne4 Bb7 {Black has to part with his dark-squared bishop} ({as} 
15... Nxe4 $2 16. Bxe4 Rb8 {pretty much loses to} 17. b4 $1 Bxb4 18. Nd4 $18 {
[%csl Rb4,Rb8,Gc6,Re7]}) 16. Nxc5 Nxc5 17. Be2 $14 {[%csl Gb7,Gd2,Ge2][%cal
Gf8d8,Ga8c8] So we have a typical position with a modest bishop pair advantage.
Black completed his development, so his position is stable, but in the long
term white should have better chances. Let us look at two examples from
practice:} Rfd8 (17... Rac8 18. Be1 {White queen looks vulnerable on c2, but
black has no dangerous discovered attacks.} Be4 19. Qc3 Qb7 20. Qa3 $1 {[%csl
Ga3] The queen feels very comfortable here.} a5 21. Bc3 Nd5 22. Bd4 {was
typically slightly better for white until black made a mistake with} Na6 $2 {
allowing the queen to penetrate his camp.} 23. Qd6 $16 {[%cal Gd6e5] 1-0 (49)
Kovalenko,I (2587)-Morozov,G (2351) Moscow 2012}) 18. Bb4 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rc8
20. Qd2 Nd5 21. Ba3 Qf6 22. Rc1 Rd8 {Now white is ready to transform one
positional advantage to another:} 23. Bxc5 bxc5 {[%csl Ra6,Rc5] 1/2-1/2
Diermair,A (2432)-Froewis,G (2329)/Linz 2011/CBM 143 Extra (27)} 24. Qa5 Rc8
25. b3 $14 {and white is slightly better due to his superior pawn structure.})
({Another interesting variation is} 10... Qe7 11. e4 e5 {the only drawback
being that the queen may be vulnerable to Nd4/Nh4-f5 jumps, just as in CHAPTER
6.} 12. h3 {[%csl Rg4,Rh2,Gh3][%cal Gh3g4] Also, just like in CHAPTER 6, white
does well with this prophylactic move.} Re8 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge8e4] This
useful move should be black's best choice since white does not seem to get
