Gf4][%cal Gf1g2]}) ({nor} 15... Bc5 16. Qe2 {[%cal Gf2f4]} Bb4 $1 {[%csl Re4]}
17. f3 c5 18. Nc2 Rxd1 19. Nxd1 $1 Ba5 20. Qf2 Ned7 21. Bf4 Ne5 22. Nce3 Bc7
23. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge3d5,Gf4g5] 1/2-1/2 Van Wely,L (2655)-Van der
Wiel,J (2525)/Leeuwarden 1997/EXT 1999 (41)}) 16. Nde2 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal
Ge2f4,Gf4d5] This is the right square for the knight as it gets a perfect
route towards d5.} c4 17. Nf4 b5 18. Ncd5 Nxd5 19. Nxd5 Qh4 20. f4 $16 {[%csl
Gd5,Ge4,Gf4] and black was strategically outplayed, so he had to resort to
dubious tactical solutions in 1-0 (60) Tsesarsky,I (2489)-Haimovich,T (2322)
Kfar Sava 2000 CBM 078 [Tsesarsky]}) ({Playing} 12... b5 {is not really
logical with black queen on e7, especially as white can keep the bishop on its
strongest diagonal} 13. Bb3 $1 $146 a5 (13... Bb7 14. Bg5 h6 15. Nh4 $1 $16)
14. a3 Bb7 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4f5] That's always going to be a
problem for black when his bishop is on b7.} Bc5 17. Nf5 Qc7 18. Bg5 Bc8 19.
Bxf6 gxf6 20. Rac1 $36) ({Finally,} 12... h6 $6 {would be very careless due to}
13. Nh4 $1 {[%cal Gh4g6,Gh4f5]}) 13. Be3 $1 exd4 14. Nxd4 {White is not
concerned about his e-pawn} Ne5 ({since} 14... Nxe4 $4 {loses to} 15. Nf5 Qe5
16. Nxe4 Qxf5 17. Bxf7+ $1 $18) 15. Bf1 Ng6 {[%csl Re4,Gf4][%cal Gd6f4] A good
move.} 16. g3 $1 {[%csl Re4] Nevertheless!} h5 $5 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gh5h4] The
position is a sort of a mix between the Reti opening and Fianchetto KID. So
black's last move makes a lot of sense.} (16... Nxe4 $6 {this time runs into}
17. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 18. Qxe4 $14 {[%csl Rd6] with advantage due to a superior
pawn structure.}) 17. Bg2 h4 18. Nf5 $1 {Strong play by white.} Bxf5 19. exf5
Ne5 {1/2-1/2 Gulko,B (2565)-Speelman,J (2630)/Reykjavik 1991/CBM 026/[Salov,V]}
{Just here he should have had no fear and play} 20. g4 $1 {which should yield
white a better position, unless black can stir up some tactical mess.} Nexg4 $5
(20... Nc4 21. Bg5 Qe5 22. Bxf6 $1 {[%cal Gc3e4]} gxf6 23. Ne4 Qh2+ 24. Kf1 $18
{[%csl Ge4,Gf1]}) 21. hxg4 Nxg4 22. Ne4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge4] This proves to be
the key defensive move and white is on top.}) ({Finally, if black puts his
queen to c7} 10... Qc7 {after} 11. Bd2 {the game will most likely transpose to
one of the other lines:} b5 (11... c5 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Bd3 {-10...c5}) 12. Bd3
c5 13. Ne4 {-10...b5}) 11. Bd3 {In general, when black plays a6 he does not
need to waste another tempo on Bb7 in order to push c6-c5. Thus, the main move
is} Qc7 ({However,} 11... Bb7 {has been seen in practice as well. Now white
has a strong reply, typical for many variations in the Meran:} 12. Ng5 $1 {
[%cal Gg5e4] At first, this might seem like a blunder since black has a small
combination that wins him a pawn. But things are not as they seem and white
has more than just compensation in that line, as we will see shortly. White
plays this move in order to bring the knight to e4 with some tempi (first on
h7, then on d6) and make black's task to free himself with c6-c5 difficult.} h6
({So if black takes the pawn} 12... Bxh2+ 13. Kxh2 Ng4+ 14. Kg1 Qxg5 {he is
first pushed back with} 15. f3 Ngf6 16. e4 Qh4 {and then has to realize that
white is about to assume complete control of the dark squares after} 17. Be3 e5
(17... Rac8 18. b4 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Gc5] solidifies white's bind.}) 18. Ne2 $1
$14 {[%csl Rb7] Black has a tough time in this kind of position despite the
extra pawn. Without the possibilty to open his light-squared bishop with c5,
he is bound to suffer without counterplay. The following examples prove that
point:} Nh5 (18... Rad8 19. b4 Rfe8 {1/2-1/2 Bruzon Batista,L (2691)-Motylev,A
(2677)/Wijk aan Zee 2012/CBM 147/[Let's Check] (61)} 20. a4 $36) 19. b4 Ng3 20.
a4 $1 Rac8 21. Qb2 exd4 22. Bxd4 f6 23. Nxg3 Qxg3 24. Bc2 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Gc2,
Gd4,Rd7][%cal Gc2b3]} Rcd8 25. Bb3+ Kh8 26. Qf2 {The endgame is even more
favorable for white as without queens black has zero counterplay.} Qb8 27. a5
$1 Ne5 28. Bb6 $16 {[%csl Gb3,Gb6,Rb7][%cal Gd1d8] 1-0 Eljanov,P (2729)
-Inarkiev,E (2645)/Khanty-Mansiysk 2009/CBM 134 (42)}) 13. Nge4 Be7 {[%csl Gc5]
[%cal Gd8b6,Gc6c5] White assumed temporary control over c5 square, but black
is threatening to bring it back with Qb6.} 14. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] If white is
allowed to push b2-b4, he would most certainly have a stable advantage.
Therefore black's most principled reply is} a5 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc6c5] The
only problem is that now b5 pawn becomes more vulnerable should black play
c6-c5. However, other moves fail to impress:} (14... Nd5 15. Nxd5 exd5 (15...
cxd5 16. Nc5 $14) 16. Ng3 a5 (16... c5 17. dxc5 Nxc5 18. Bf5 $14) 17. Nf5 $14 {
1-0 Khismatullin,D (2646)-Geller,J (2559)/Moscow RUS 2012/The Week in Chess
940 (63)}) (14... Qb8 15. b4 a5 16. Rb1 axb4 17. axb4 {[%csl Rb7]} Nd5 {[%cal
Gd5b4]} 18. Nc5 Nxc5 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. dxc5 Rd8 21. e4 $1 dxe4 22. Bxe4 Rxd1+
23. Qxd1 Qe5 24. Qc2 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6] 1-0 Wojtaszek,R (2711)-Van Wely,L 
(2679)/Khanty-Mansiysk 2010/CBM 139 (45)}) 15. Bd2 {As in most of the other
lines in this chapter, this move is white's best way to complete development.}
Qb6 16. Nxf6+ Nxf6 17. Rab1 {Repeating the positional threat b2-b4. Black has
several options to deal with it:} c5 {This pawn sacrifice looks like black's
best bid at activity.} (17... a4 {is the least impressive as white has} 18. Ne4
Nxe4 19. Bxe4 {[%cal Gd2b4] with a powerful idea Bb4 Bxb4 axb4 and the pawn
reaches b4 anyway! Black decided to stop it with} b4 20. axb4 Bxb4 21. Ra1 Bxd2
22. Rxd2 $16 {[%csl Ra4,Rb7,Rc6][%cal Gd2d3,Gd3c3] but his structural problems
remained in 1/2-1/2 Pashikian,A (2640)-Andriasian,Z (2585)/Yerevan 2011/CBM
141 (36)}) (17... b4 {solves the problem of b4, but not of c5.} 18. Na4 Qa7 19.
axb4 axb4 20. Nc5 Bxc5 21. dxc5 {[%csl Rb4]}) 18. dxc5 Qc6 $5 19. Bf1 Qxc5 20.
Bxb5 {[%csl Gb7,Gc5][%cal Gb7g2] White wins a pawn. Black is however, very
active and can count on at least temporary compensation. In the following game
he tried to get more, but ultimately failed to do so.} Rac8 (20... Qg5 21. Bf1
Bf3 22. Rdc1 Bd6 23. g3 $14 {[%cal Gf1g2]}) 21. Qa4 Rfd8 22. Be1 Bd6 23. Qh4
Qf5 24. Be2 $14 {[%csl Ge1,Ge2,Gh4] White consolidated his extra pawn. He
should now look to make use of it and this is exactly what he did:} Qc2 25. Bd3
Qb3 26. Rd2 Be7 27. Bc2 Qb6 28. Rxd8+ Rxd8 29. Qa4 Bc6 30. Qc4 Qb7 31. e4 $1
Ng4 32. Qe2 Ne5 33. b4 $1 $16 {[%csl Gb4] and white was finally on his way to
victory in 1-0 Gustafsson,J (2643)-Kuipers,S (2391)/Caleta 2012/CBM 147 (53)})
({Let's just also state the obvious that the immediate} 11... c5 $6 {is too
risky due to} 12. Ne4 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Rc5,Rd6,Rh7]}) 12. Bd2 {[%cal Gb2b4] As
usual, we bring the bishop out to d2. This time, it also contains a strong
positional threat b2-b4.} c5 {Black should play this move given a chance.} ({
Here is what happens if he hesitates:} 12... Bb7 13. b4 $1 $14 {[%csl Gb4,Rb7]
creating the bind as the pawn is indirectly protected by the d2 bishop.} e5 {
With c6-c5 disabled, black usually turns to the other central break.} (13...
Bxb4 $6 {would be quite bad for black due to} 14. Nxb5 $1 axb5 15. Bxb4 $16 {
[%csl Rb7,Gc5,Rc6]}) ({Another attempt is to weaken the b4 pawn with} 13... a5
14. a3 axb4 15. axb4 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc2b3] However, it will have sufficient
protection.} h6 (15... e5 16. h3 Rfe8 17. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gg5e4] The
well-known maneuvre works well here too.} h6 18. Nge4 exd4 19. exd4 Rxa1 20.
Rxa1 Bxb4 $6 {This loses a pawn, though the position was not a bed of roses
anyway.} 21. Nxb5 Qb8 22. Nxf6+ Nxf6 23. Bxb4 cxb5 24. Bxb5 $16 {0-1 Demianjuk,
A (2312)-Duzhakov,I (2347)/Voronezh 2011/CBM 143 Extra (50)}) 16. Rac1 Qb6 17.
Qb3 Ra6 18. e4 {[%csl Gb4,Gd4,Ge4] With the b-pawn safely defended, white can
turn his attention to central operations.} e5 19. Ne2 Rfa8 20. Bc3 Ra3 21. Qb1
$14 {1-0 Cheparinov,I (2650)-Coleman,T (2312)/Bastia 2011/EXT 2012 (33)}) 14.
Rac1 Rfe8 ({In the following game black tried to force his way out of the bind
with} 14... exd4 15. exd4 c5 $6 {but this smells of desparation} 16. bxc5 Bxf3
17. gxf3 Bxh2+ 18. Kg2 $40 {and in fact it gave white the attack!} Bf4 $2 19.
Bxh7+ $1 Nxh7 20. Nd5 Qd8 21. Bxf4 $18 {1-0 Wagner,D (2465)-Boehm,R (2178)/
Dresden 2013/CBM 155 Extra (35)}) 15. Qb1 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rc7] with a nice edge
for white. Black's position is solid, but cramped.} h6 16. h3 exd4 17. exd4 Nb6
18. Re1 {Necessary regrouping after the e-file has opened.} Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Bc8
{In general the plan to reactivate the bishop is good, though it is
time-consuming.} 20. Qc1 $1 {[%csl Rg8,Rh6][%cal Gd2h6] Eyeing the kingside.}
Bf8 21. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5]} Be6 22. a3 Rc8 23. Ne2 $1 $36 {[%cal Ge2f4,Ge2g3]
with a strong pressure in 1-0 Kuljasevic,D (2537)-Zelbel,P (2428)/Pula 2011/
CBM 143 Extra (32)}) ({Let it just be noted why} 12... e5 $6 {does not work
here:} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. f4 $1 Bd6 16. Ne4 $36 {[%csl Rc6,Rd6,
Ge4,Gf4,Rf6,Rh7] That's why black usually waits for white to push e4 first and
then plays e5.}) 13. Ne4 $1 {The most ambitious continuation, introduced by GM
Wojtaszek.} (13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. a4 {is possible too, but is not as promising if
black defends accurately.} ({or} 14. Ne4)) 13... c4 {This could be the only
objection to Ne4 because black wins a tempo and gets control of the
light-squares in the center. However, as we will see, white has his own
long-term trumps.} ({Less logical seems to be} 13... cxd4 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 {as
white obtains the bishop pair in an open position. Black is nevertheless quite
solid here and white can count on a small advantage only. I prefer} 15. Nxd4 ({
over} 15. Be4 Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Bb7 $1 17. Qxb7 Nc5 18. Bb4 $1 Nxb7 19. Bxd6 Nxd6
20. Rxd4 $14 {which happened in 1-0 Sargissian,G (2683)-Nezad,H (2402)/Caleta
2012/CBM 147 (45). White enjoys a slight pressure in the endgame, but I have a
feeling that black can equalize with precise defense.}) 15... Bb7 16. Be2 Rfc8
17. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Gd2,Ge2] White has a typical small advantage that we have
seen in positions from 10...c5 line. In the only game played here, black made
a positional mistake offering queen trade:} Qd5 $6 (17... Nc5 18. Qa3 $14 {
[%csl Ga3]}) 18. f3 Nb6 19. Qxd5 Bxd5 20. b3 g6 21. e4 $16 {with complete
domination in 1-0 Farago,I (2443)-Namyslo,H (2211)/Dresden 2014/CBM 161 Extra 
(31)}) (13... Bb7 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Qxc5 Nxc5 17. Be2 {
transposes to 10...c5}) 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Be2 Bb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gc4,Yd2,Gd5,Ge4]
Black has full light-square control which compensates for white's supremacy on
the dark-squares. Strategic battles of this type are often waged in the
Nimzo-Indian defense.} 16. b3 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb3c4] It is absolutely
necessary for white to challenge black pawn on c4 to get more maneuvering
space.} Rfc8 {This is the most common response.} ({White would get a
significant relief after} 16... cxb3 $6 17. axb3 $14 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Ga1a6,
Gc1c8] when all his pieces become alive. Black should keep the pawn on c4 as
long as possible to restrict white's possibilities.}) ({Another common move is
} 16... Bd5 17. Qb2 {[%cal Gf3e5]} Ne4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Ge4]} 18. Be1 {[%csl Ge1,
Ge2] White should, of course, preserve his bishop pair if he hopes to get any
advantage.} (18. Ba5 {has been played, too. Differences between these two
moves are ever so subtle, so I will not dwell on them. One thing that should
be remembered is that black often tries to sideline the bishop on a5 with} cxb3
19. axb3 b4 {[%csl Ra5]}) 18... Rfc8 ({Playing in the Dutch style} 18... f5 $6
{is not good as white has} 19. Ne5 $16 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf2f3]}) 19. Rac1 {and
we transpose to the line where black plays 16...Rfc8, followed by 17...Bd5.}) (
{Bringing the bishop to e4} 16... Be4 $6 {is pointless. White quickly gets
what he wants:} 17. Qb2 Rfc8 18. Ne1 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf2f3,Ge3e4]} Nd5 19.
Rac1 {[%csl Rc4]} cxb3 20. axb3 Bg6 21. Nd3 {[%csl Gd3]} f6 22. Nc5 $1 Nxc5 23.
dxc5 $16 {[%csl Ga5,Gb4,Gb6,Gc5,Gd2,Gd6] once white pieces begin to penetrate
dark squares, black has lost the strategic battle. 1-0 Farago,I (2497)
-Hertneck,G (2531)/Austria 2012/CBM 146 Extra (66)}) ({Finally,} 16... Rac8 {
that was played in 1-0 Predke,A (2464)-Frolyanov,D (2564)/Samara 2012/CBM 149
Extra (39) is less accurate than Rfc8 because of} 17. bxc4 $146 bxc4 18. Rdc1
Bd5 19. Qa4 $1 $36 {[%csl Ra6,Rc4][%cal Gd2b4] when the rook on f8 is
misplaced.}) 17. Qb2 Rab8 {[%cal Gb8b2] This is the most efficient way to
defend the c-pawn, using the position of white queen on b2.} (17... Bd5 {[%csl
Gd5] is the main alternative.} 18. Rac1 Ne4 19. Be1 f6 {[%csl Ge5] White
wanted to play Ne5, so black stops it.} (19... Rab8 20. Ne5 $36 {[%cal Gf2f3]})
(19... Qe7 20. Rc2 $14 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd1c1]}) 20. Ba5 $1 {[%cal Gf3e1,Gf2f3]
Clearing the e1 square for the knight now that Ne5 is not possible any more.
After all, it was useful to provoke weakening of black's structure.f7-f6.} Rab8
({If black tries to cut off the bishop with} 20... cxb3 21. axb3 b4 {[%csl Ra5,
Gc3][%cal Ge4c3] white should react calmly} 22. Bf1 Nc3 23. Re1 {[%cal Gf3d2]}
Bxf3 24. gxf3 $16 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gf1c4] Black can not really trap the bishop
on a5 and actually he needs to worry about defending his b4 pawn. The c3
knight is just for show.}) 21. Ne1 f5 22. f3 Nef6 23. Nc2 $1 $14 {[%csl Gb4,
Gc3,Ge4] White is maneuvering well in a tight space. He covers all the
important squares, thus his position is preferable. Two games were played from
this position, both ending successfully for white player.} cxb3 (23... Kf7 24.
Be1 g5 25. Bb4 Qc6 26. Rf1 $1 Qb6 27. Qa3 $16 {1-0 Stremavicius,T (2457)
-Loetscher,R (2439)/Panevezys 2015/EXT 2016 (38)}) 24. axb3 Bb7 25. Nb4 Nd5 26.
Qd2 f4 27. e4 Ne3 28. Re1 Ne5 29. Rc3 Ng6 30. Rec1 $16 {1-0 Bukavshin,I (2629)
-Artemiev,V (2660)/Khanty-Mansiysk 2014/EXT 2015 (79)}) 18. Rac1 Ne4 {The
standard follow-up.} ({In a relatively recent game, black tried a new idea:} 
18... Ng4 $5 19. h3 Bxf3 20. Bxf3 Qh2+ 21. Kf1 Ngf6 {and now instead of} 22.
bxc4 $2 ({White should have played} 22. Ke2 $146 {[%csl Ge2] the king is not
endangered here.} Qd6 ({preventing} 22... e5 23. Rh1 $18 {[%csl Rh2]}) 23. e4
$14 {[%csl Gd2,Gd4,Ge4,Gf3] I like white here very much.}) 22... e5 $1 23. c5
e4 24. Bg4 Nxg4 25. hxg4 Nf6 $17 {0-1 Duda,J (2632)-Ter Sahakyan,S (2593)/
Martuni 2015/CBM 168 (74)}) ({We can see what happens if black underestimates
Nf3-e5:} 18... h6 $6 19. Ne5 $36 {[%csl Rc4]} cxb3 20. axb3 Rxc1 21. Rxc1 Nxe5
22. dxe5 Qd5 23. f3 Ng4 {Karjakin was probably counting on this counterattack,
but he did not calculate far enough:} 24. Bb4 $1 Rd8 25. Bd6 {[%csl Rd5]} Nxe3
26. Rc5 {trapping the queen in the middle of the board!} Rxd6 27. Rxd5 Rxd5 28.
Qc3 $16 {1-0 Jakovenko,D (2738)-Karjakin,S (2753)/Khanty-Mansiysk 2015/CBM 167
(65)}) {Here I would recommend an improvement} 19. Ba5 $1 $146 {[%cal Gf3e1,
Gf2f3] where white plans to continue Ne1, f3 etc.} ({over the stem game:} 19.
Be1 Nb6 20. Ba5 cxb3 21. axb3 b4 $1 22. Rxc8+ Rxc8 23. Rc1 {1-0 Wojtaszek,R 
(2711)-Smeets,J (2669)/Solingen GER 2011/The Week in Chess 851 (32)} {where
black could have gotten good counterplay with} Nc3 $1 24. Bf1 Bxf3 25. gxf3 $13
) 19... Bd5 {It seems that transposing to the position that we analyzed in 17..
.Bd5 variation (game Bukavshin-Artemiev, 2014.) is black's safest option.
Other plans are either too risky,} ({such as} 19... Qd5 20. bxc4 bxc4 21. Qa3
c3 22. Rc2 $16 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gd1c1]}) ({too slow} 19... Nb6 20. Ne1 $16 {
[%cal Gf2f3]}) ({or can be refuted by precise play, like} 19... cxb3 20. axb3
b4 21. Rxc8+ Rxc8 22. Bc4 $1 Nc3 (22... Bd5 23. Rc1 $1 Nc3 24. Bxb4 Qxb4 25.
Qxc3 Qxc3 26. Rxc3 $16) 23. Rc1 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Rc3][%cal Ga5b4]}) 20. Ne1 f5
21. f3 Nef6 22. Nc2 $14 {with a clear advantage for white. Please see
annotations to 17...Bd5 for details.} *

