1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O
dxc4 9. Bxc4 {In this short chapter we will take a look at rare 9th move
alternatives for black. The thing about sidelines is that white usually does
not have to work that hard to obtain the advantage out of the opening. Still,
precision is needed as any step in a wrong direction in an opening as sound as
the Semi-Slav may allow black to equalize. Let us start with the relatively
most popular:} Qe7 ({In CHAPTER 7 we have already seen positions where black
tries to equalize with} 9... c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 {Here however, c6-c5 is a bit
premature as white can play} 11. e4 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge4e5] threatening to
take up space with e4-e5.} Qc7 {[%csl Ge5]} ({The other way to cover e5 is} 
11... Ng4 12. Bf4 Qf6 {[%csl Ge5]} 13. Bg3 Nge5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Be2 Nc6 {
[%cal Gc6d4]} ({Black does not have time to complete his development} 15... Bd7
{due to} 16. Nd5 $1 exd5 17. Qxc5 $16) 16. e5 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gc3e4]} Qe7
17. Qe4 $40 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge2d3,Gg3h4] and white achieved a typical
attacking setup in 1-0 Grischuk,A (2746)-Genba,V (2452)/Khanty-Mansiysk 2011/
CBM 145 (23)}) 12. Qe2 {[%cal Ge4e5]} Ne5 {This is the best way to deal with
white's threat.} ({Less impressive is} 12... Ng4 13. Bb3 a6 14. h3 Nge5 15.
Nxe5 Nxe5 16. Bf4 Bd6 17. Rac1 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1c7] black is always just
one move short of completing his development.} Qb8 18. Be3 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4]}
Bd7 19. f4 Ng6 20. e5 Bc7 21. Ne4 $36 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5,Gf4] and white achieved
his ideal in 1/2-1/2 Malaniuk,V (2600)-Lau,R (2530)/Dortmund 1993/TD (41)}) (
12... e5 {prevents e4-e5, but creates new weaknesses} 13. Bg5 $36 {[%csl Gd5]
[%cal Gc4f7]}) 13. Bf4 Bd6 $1 {[%cal Gc7c4] This is an improvement by GM
Sjugirov} ({over} 13... Nxf3+ 14. Qxf3 e5 15. Bg5 $14 Be7 {[%cal Gc8e6] 1-0
Kantsler,B (2519)-Lederman,L (2346)/Israel 2002/EXT 2003 (41)} {white had a
very strong resource:} 16. Rfc1 $1 $36 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1c7] since} Qxc4 {
loses to} 17. Nd5 Qxc1+ 18. Bxc1 $1 $18) 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Qxe5 {Black
seems to be close to achieving equality, thus I believe white should not waste
any time and play} 16. f4 $146 ({Draw was agreed after} 16. Qe3 {in 1/2-1/2
Khairullin,I (2629)-Sjugirov,S (2678)/Jerusalem 2015/CBM 166 and rightfully so,
as after} Bd7 17. Be2 Bc6 18. Rfd1 Rfd8 19. f3 a6 $11 {black would complete
his development and would have no problems in a weakness-free position.}) 16...
Qc5+ 17. Kh1 e5 ({Allowing e4-e5 is again not recommended for black:} 17... Bd7
18. e5 Rfc8 19. Bd3 Nd5 20. Nxd5 exd5 (20... Qxd5 21. Rfd1 Qc6 22. Be4 $18 {
[%csl Rd7,Rh7]}) 21. f5 $40 {[%csl Ge5,Gf5]}) 18. f5 {[%csl Rc8,Gf5] White
gains space on the kingside.} Bd7 {and here the most consistent is} 19. g4 $1 {
[%csl Gd5][%cal Gg4g5]} h6 (19... Nxg4 $6 20. Qxg4 Qxc4 {would be super-risky
because it gives white an open g-file and d5 square for attack} 21. Rg1 {[%cal
Gg1g7]} g6 22. Nd5 $40 {[%csl Ge7,Gf6,Rg8]}) 20. Rg1 $40 {[%csl Rg8][%cal
Gg4g5] with an unpleasant position to defend for black.}) ({Another rare move
where black is not showing his cards is} 9... Qc7 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gb7b5] keeping
both e6-e5 and b7-b5 as options. We have seen in CHAPTER 7 that the position
of queen on c7 gives white some tactical ideas along the c-file, thus I would
recommend a rare, but logical move} 10. Bd2 $5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c7]
expediting doubling of heavy pieces on the c-file.} e5 {The most principled
reaction to Bd2.} ({If black focuses on the other side of the board with either
} 10... a6 11. Rac1 b5 (11... h6 {is solid, but slow} 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Qxe4 $14
{[%cal Gc4d3] giving white a pleasant edge in 1-0 Peng,Z (2472)-Bensdorp,M 
(2125)/Leeuwarden 2002/CBM 088 Extra (63) since black has difficulties
realizing his pawn breaks. For example:} e5 14. Qg6 $1) 12. Bd3 {and if black
insists on} c5 $6 (12... Bb7 13. b4 $14 {with a bind that we have seen in
CHAPTER 7.}) 13. Ne4 c4 14. b3 $16 {[%csl Gc1] he gets a worse version of a
similar position from the previous chapter.}) ({or} 10... b5 11. Bd3 Bb7 12.
Rac1 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc3b5]} a6 13. b4 $1 $14 {White has an extra tempo as he
did not have to play Rfd1, so black is not in time to organize his c6-c5 push.}
) 11. h3 exd4 (11... b5 12. Bd3 exd4 13. exd4 Bb7 {was played in 1/2-1/2
Eingorn,V (2545)-Jussupow,A (2645)/Minsk 1987/URS-ch} {and here with could get
a firm grip on the position with simple} 14. Rfe1 a6 15. b4 $14 {[%csl Rb7]})
12. exd4 Nb6 13. Bb3 {[%csl Rc8] We have seen similar positions in CHAPTER 6
and concluded that unless black can develop his light-squared bishop
comfortably, white will keep a small advantage. This position is not an
exception, as following variations show:} Bf4 (13... h6 $4 14. Bxh6 gxh6 15.
Qg6+ Kh8 16. Qxf6+ {1-0 Lukacs,P (2475)-Barczay,L (2420)/Budapest 1998/EXT 1999
}) (13... Nbd5 14. Rae1 $14 Be6 15. Ng5 {[%csl Re6] and black has problems
with his bishop again since} Nb4 $6 {is dubious} 16. Nxe6 Nxc2 17. Nxc7 Nxe1
18. Nxa8) (13... g6 $5 {[%csl Rf6,Rh6][%cal Gc8f5] actually enables black to
develop the bishop to a good square, but also weakens his own king.} 14. Bh6
Bf5 15. Qd2 Rfe8 16. Rfe1 $14) 14. Rac1 Bxd2 15. Qxd2 Qd6 16. Rfe1 h6 17. Re5
Rd8 18. Rce1 $36 {[%csl Gb3,Rc8,Ge5][%cal Ge1e8] 1-0 Smejkal,J (2525)-Saljova,
S (2225)/Pribram 1998/EXT 2000 (27)}) (9... h6 {is a rare waiting move. White
obtains advantage with relatively straight-forward play:} 10. Rd1 Qc7 (10...
Qe7 {surprisingly allows white to develop serious initiative with} 11. e4 e5
12. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Rd6,Re7,Rf8][%cal Gh4f5,Gh4g6]} Nb6 {The only move. Now we
enter a more or less forced line:} 13. Ng6 Qc7 14. dxe5 Bxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16.
Be2 Ng4 17. Bxg4 Bxg4 18. f3 Qc5+ 19. Qf2 Qxf2+ 20. Kxf2 $14 {reaching the
endgame where white holds a solid advantage.} Be6 21. b3 {[%csl Gc1,Re6][%cal
Gc1a3,Gc1e3,Ge3f4] Black bishop is restricted by white pawns, while white
bishop has several promising diagonals.} ({I would actually prefer} 21. g4 $14
{to make sure black never plays f7-f5 which would free his position somewhat.})
21... Rfd8 22. Be3 Kf8 (22... f5 $142) 23. h3 Ke8 24. f4 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 f6 26.
f5 $16 {[%csl Re6,Rg7] 1-0 Duer,W (2280)-Schmidlechner,A (2255)/Austria 1996/
EXT 1998 (45)}) {Just like in 9...Qc7 line, the queen on c7 is a signal for}
11. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c7]} e5 12. Rac1 exd4 13. exd4 Nb6 14. Bb3
{The only drawback of this line is that white does not have h3 so black can
play} Bg4 ({or} 14... Bf4 15. Re1 $14 Bg4 16. Ne4 $1 Nfd5 17. Bxf4 Qxf4 18. Ne5
$36) {but then white could spring a nasty surprise on him:} 15. Bxh6 $1 $146 ({
instead of} 15. Nb5 Qd8 16. Nxd6 Qxd6 17. Qd3 Nbd5 18. Re1 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 {
which ended peacefully in 1/2-1/2 Curic,D (2264)-Jelecevic,I (2183)/Zagreb
2011/CBM 141 Extra}) 15... Bxf3 16. Qg6 $1 {and here black has to find the
only moves} Bxh2+ 17. Kh1 Ne8 18. gxf3 Qd6 $1 19. Qxd6 Bxd6 {in hopes to
survive a worse endgame after} 20. Rg1 $14) {Black's last move was quite
flexible, inviting white into several tricky transpositions. The move that I
found to be the most flexible in response and also the most consistent with
white's play in other branches of the Meran is} 10. h3 c5 {Objectively
speaking, not the best, but in this chapter I wanted to cover all the
independent tries that do not actually transpose into lines that we already
analyzed.} ({Probably the best is} 10... e5 {transposing into CHAPTER 6.}) ({
While} 10... a6 {transposes into CHAPTER 7 after} 11. e4 e5 12. Rd1) (10... b5
{is another independent idea. Here white continues} 11. Be2 a6 12. e4 e5 13.
Rd1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd1d6] This move is often useful in variations with b7-b5
as it puts an eye on the Bd6.} Bb7 ({If} 13... Re8 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge8e4]
white can be subtle about his bishop's development with} 14. Bg5 $1 {provoking}
h6 15. Be3 {[%csl Rh6] so that black can not play g6 to defend f5 square due
to the weakness of h6 pawn:} Bb7 16. dxe5 $1 Nxe5 17. Nd4 {[%csl Gf5,Rh6][%cal
Rg7g6]}) 14. dxe5 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Gf5][%cal Gf3d4,Gd4f5] Once the bishop is on
b7, white should shift his focus to f5 square.} Nxe5 15. Nd4 Bc5 {1-0
Arutinian,D (2444)-Kotanjian,T (2452)/Moscow 2004/EXT 2005} {and here simply}
16. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gd4f5,Gf2f4] was giving white the advantage.}) 11. dxc5 Bxc5
12. e4 $1 {[%csl Re7,Gh3][%cal Rf6g4] We have already seen this idea in 9...c5
variation. This time it comes in an even better version because h3 is useful
to cover g4 and also black queen is not placed so well on e7.} Bd6 13. Nb5 $1
$36 {[%csl Gb5] The key move that gives white a strong initiative. This is why
black like to play a6 (to cover b5 square) before they push c6-c5.} Ne5 (13...
Bb8 14. b3 $1 {[%cal Gc1a3]} b6 15. e5 $1 {[%csl Ge5]} Nd5 16. Ba3 Nc5 17. Bxd5
exd5 18. Rac1 $16 {1-0 Uhlmann,W (2480)-Schlosser,P (2500)/Baden-Baden 1992/
CBM 033 (62)}) 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. f4 {This forces black into the following line:
} Qc5+ 16. Kh2 Bd7 17. b4 $1 Qb6 18. fxe5 Bxb5 19. exf6 {Only one look at the
position is enough to see that black will fall under attack even after
returning the piece.} Qc7+ (19... Rfc8 20. Qd2 $1 Bxc4 21. Qg5 g6 22. Rf4 $40 {
1-0 Ruzele,D (2520)-Delemarre,J (2360)/Groningen 1996/EXT 1998 (27)}) 20. Rf4
$1 Bxc4 21. fxg7 Rfd8 22. Be3 Rd3 23. Qf2 $16 {1-0 Ehlvest,J (2635)-Galliamova,
A (2440)/Pula 1997/EXT 2000 (48)} *

