1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O ({
Sometimes black play dxc4 and b5 as soon as white brings his bishop out to d3.
} 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 b5 9. Be2 {At this point black usually castle and the game
transposes to the main lines, but sometimes (especially in blitz games) they
try to surprise white with} Bb7 10. O-O a6 {[%cal Gc6c5] going for the quick
c6-c5 by the virtue of saved tempo (on 0-0). However, there is a small hole in
this plan that white can take advantage of:} 11. e4 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nh4 $1
$146 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gh4f5,Gf2f4] We already know that f5 square is
vulnerable when black bishop leaves c8-h3 diagonal. Additionally, with his
last move white made dangerous f2-f4 push possible.} ({Less convincing was} 13.
Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Be3 O-O 15. f4 Bd4 16. Bxd4 Qxd4+ 17. Kh1 b4 $1 18. e5 bxc3 19.
bxc3 Qd8 20. exf6 Qxf6 $11 {1/2-1/2 Feller,S (2657)-Vallejo Pons,F (2707)/Aix
les Bains 2011/CBM 142 Extra}) 13... Bc8 {If black has to play this move, it
means that something has gone wrong. However, other moves allow white to
develop an even stronger initiative.} (13... g6 $6 14. f4 Bc5+ 15. Kh1 Neg4 16.
e5 $1 Nf2+ 17. Rxf2 Bxf2 18. Nf3 Nd7 19. Ne4 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Gd6,Re8,Rf2][%cal
Ge4d6,Ge4f2] we can see in this variation how delaying 0-0 can backfire on
black.}) (13... O-O 14. Nf5 Bc5 15. Bg5 $36 {[%csl Gf5,Gg5][%cal Gg5d8]}) 14.
Kh1 $1 {[%csl Gh1][%cal Gf2f4] A prudent move, avoiding checks along the g1-a7
diagonal.} (14. f4 {is far less clear:} Ng6 15. e5 (15. Nxg6 Bc5+ $1 16. Kh1
hxg6 $132) 15... Nxh4 16. exf6 O-O 17. fxg7 Re8 $1 $13 {[%cal Gc8f5]}) 14...
O-O (14... Nfg4 15. g3) 15. f4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] white can claim the advantage
after this move, though of course position remains complex:} Nfg4 $1 16. Nf3
Nxf3 17. gxf3 $1 {An unorthodox, but right decision in this particular
position. The knight will be kicked back to the margins.} Nh6 18. f5 {[%csl
Ge4,Gf3,Gf5,Rh6][%cal Gc1h6,Rf1g1,Rg1g7] And as a result of gxf3 white got a
strong pawn mass and a g-file for attack.} Qh4 19. Bd3 $36 {[%cal Gc2g2,Gf1g1]}
) 8. O-O dxc4 9. Bxc4 {Over the course of the previous few chapters we have
seen many different possibilities for black in this position. The one that we
have left for the end is} b5 {which is the most direct and most popular move.
White can retreat his bishop to d3 or e2. I would recommend} 10. Be2 {Now
before we move on to the main line 10...Bb7 which is covered in CHAPTER 10,
let us see which alternatives black has:} a6 {This is the most significant
alternative to Bb7 and it is perhaps not any worse. The idea is to prepare
c6-c5 keeping the bishop on c8 for the time being.} ({Other alternatives are a
bit less explored. The one that gained popularity recently is} 10... Qe7 11.
Rd1 a6 (11... Bb7 12. e4 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nd4 $14) {and here white can
play the same way as against 10...a6:} 12. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5e4]} c5 13. Nce4 Bb7
14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. dxc5 Qxc5 16. Qxc5 Nxc5 17. Bd2 {[%csl Gd2,Ge2] gaining the
well-known small bishop pair advantage in the endgame.} Rfc8 {In the game 1-0 
(59) Caprio,G (2401)-Adhiban,B (2630) Doha QAT 2014} {the most accurate was}
18. Rdc1 $14) ({The other way to develop the queen is} 10... Qc7 {when you can
probably already guess white's response:} 11. Bd2 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c7]
} Bb7 (11... a6 12. b4 e5 13. Bd3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge4] white can afford to waste a
tempo in such a closed position.} exd4 14. exd4 Bb7 15. a3 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6]
We have seen similar positions before. White holds a positional advantage.} h6
16. Rac1 Nb6 17. Ne2 Nbd5 18. Qb3 Bc8 19. Bb1 Be6 20. Qc2 Ne7 21. Ng3 Bd5 22.
Ne5 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd2c3] 1/2-1/2 Farago,I (2506)-Jakab,A (2396)/Budapest 2002/
CBM 087 Extra (35)}) (11... Re8 12. Rac1 Qb8 {was quite passive and Karpov
took advantage of it instructively:} 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 Bb7 15. Qh4 (15. Bd3
$5 {[%csl Rg8] was a more aggresive option.}) 15... h6 16. Rfd1 a5 17. Be1 Qd8
18. Qxd8 Rexd8 19. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ge2f3,Gd2e4]} a4 20. Bf3 $14 {[%csl
Rb7,Rc6] This kind of position was Karpov's bread and butter back in the day.}
Ra6 21. Ne4 Be7 22. a3 $1 {[%cal Ge1b4]} Ra7 23. Bb4 Bxb4 24. axb4 $16 {[%csl
Rb7,Gc5,Rc6] with a complete positional domination in 1-0 Karpov,A (2725)-Van
der Wiel,J (2540)/Tilburg 1988/CBM 009 (44)}) 12. Rac1 a6 13. b4 Rfe8 14. h3
Rac8 {this happened in 1/2-1/2 Huebner,R (2604)-Shabalov,A (2597)/Willemstad
2003/EXT 2004 (52) and here the most promising was} 15. Bd3 e5 16. a3 h6 17.
Rfe1 exd4 18. exd4 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Gf5] with a typical small advantage for
white.}) (10... Re8 {is either a very deep move or a waste of time. Either way,
white should continue:} 11. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8]} Qc7 {and using the same logic
from the previous variation, he should not even think twice about} 12. Bd2 a6
13. Rac1 ({An interesting thought is} 13. Bd3 $5 {which transposes to CHAPTER
7, only with rook on e8 instead of f8. In the main line with} c5 ({In case of} 
13... Bb7 14. b4 e5 15. Rac1 exd4 16. exd4 $14 {[%cal Ge8e1] the rook makes
more sense on e8, though it does not change the character of the position.})
14. Ne4 c4 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. Be2 Bb7 17. b3 {[%csl Ge8] The position of the
rook on e8 does not seem to make any difference whatsoever. Black tends to
bring his rook to c8 in that line anyway, so it does not matter whether it
came from f8 or e8.}) 13... c5 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Be1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd1d6] A
quiet move that creates contact on d6} Be7 ({so black can not complete
development with} 15... Bb7 {due to} 16. Qd2 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gd2d6,Gc1c6]})
16. b4 $1 {An excellent way to keep the initiative.} Qb6 17. a4 Bxb4 (17...
bxa4 18. Nxa4 Qa7 19. Nc5 $16 {[%csl Ra8,Gc5,Rc8,Re8] would be an awful
position for black.}) 18. Rb1 $1 Bxc3 19. Qxc3 {[%csl Ge1,Ge2][%cal Ga4b5] now
white will enjoy the advantage of bishop pair in an open position. The pawn on
b5 will be regained.} Nd5 20. Qc1 Bb7 21. axb5 a5 $6 {[%csl Ra5,Gb5] This is a
dubious positional decision, leaving white with a powerful pawn and keeping a
bad one.} ({Black probably disliked} 21... axb5 22. Bxb5 Rec8 23. Qd2 Bc6 24.
Bf1 Qa7 25. Rdc1 $36 {where his pieces lack good squares.}) 22. Qa3 $16 {[%csl
Ra5] 1-0 Fressinet,L (2676)-Ruck,R (2574)/Germany 2009/CBM 128 Extra (41)}) {
White has tried several plans against black's solid setup over the years.
Lately an interesting new way was introduced.} 11. Ng5 $5 {We have seen this
idea before, but with bishop on d3. Not that it was any dangerous, but here
black does not even have the option Bxh2 and Ng4. The most critical
continuation is still the one that targets weakened h2 pawn:} Qc7 {[%csl Rh2]}
(11... h6 {is a bit too cooperative as white wanted to play} 12. Nge4 {anyway.}
Be7 13. Rd1 Qc7 14. Bd2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge4c5,Ga1c1] Standard plan for white
with an added benefit of having the knight on e4 to control c5 square.} Bb7 (
14... c5 $6 {was timed badly:} 15. dxc5 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 f5 17. Ng3 Qxc5 18. Qb3
$16 {[%csl Re6] and ended with a blunder} Qb6 $2 19. Ba5 $1 {[%csl Re6] 1-0
Khairullin,I (2629)-Kjartansson,G (2484)/Jerusalem 2015/CBM 166}) 15. b4 Rac8
16. a3 e5 17. Rac1 Rfd8 18. Ng3 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Gf5][%cal Gg3f5] was another
day in the office in 1-0 Parligras,M (2586)-Petrosyan,T (2469)/Al-Ain UAE 2015/
The Week in Chess 1104 (33)}) ({One game also saw} 11... Bb7 {when I think
white can play even more ambitiously} 12. e4 $1 $146 {[%cal Ge4e5]} ({than} 12.
Nce4 Be7 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 14. Bd2 {which lead to a positional battle for c5
square in which black eventually prevailed:} b4 15. Bd3 h6 16. Nh7 Nxh7 17.
Bxh7+ Kh8 18. Be4 Qb6 19. Rfc1 Rac8 20. Qb3 a5 21. Qa4 Rfd8 22. Be1 Rc7 23. a3
c5 $11 {1/2-1/2 Pashikian,A (2614)-Hovhannisyan,R (2594)/Yerevan 2015/CBM 165})
12... c5 $5 {Sharp, but insufficient for equality.} ({The positions similar to
} 12... e5 13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. f4 $36 {are discussed below.}) 13. e5 cxd4 14.
exf6 Nxf6 15. Nce4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Bxh2+ 17. Kxh2 Qh4+ 18. Kg1 Bxe4 19. Qd2 $14 {
White's piece should be more meaningful than black's pawns.}) 12. e4 $1 {[%cal
Ge4e5] White's previous move would make little sense without this enterprising
pawn sacrifice.} Bxh2+ {Again, the most principled.} ({The alternatives are} 
12... h6 13. e5 hxg5 14. exd6 Qxd6 15. Bxg5 Qxd4 {[%csl Rc8,Ge2,Gg5][%cal
Ga1d1] where black is also pawn up, but white gets a really nice free piece
play. The bishop pair does not hurt his chances either. From this position we
have two games, both ending in white's favor:} 16. h4 $5 {[%csl Rg8][%cal
Gh4h5,Gh5h6] A cool idea.} (16. Rad1 Qc5 17. Be3 Qf5 18. Bd3 Qh5 19. Ne4 {
[%csl Rc8,Gd3,Ge3,Ge4]} Ng4 20. Bf4 f5 21. Nd6 g5 22. h3 gxf4 23. hxg4 fxg4 24.
Bg6 Qg5 25. Rfe1 $36 {[%csl Gc2,Gd1,Gd6,Ge1,Gg6] 1-0 Gordievsky,D (2506)
-Inarkiev,E (2676)/Moscow RUS 2016/The Week in Chess 1109 (40)}) 16... Bb7 17.
Rad1 Qc5 18. Qd2 b4 19. Na4 Qa5 20. b3 c5 21. h5 $1 c4 22. Qe3 $1 $40 {[%cal
Gh5h6] threatening to launch a strong kingside attack in 1-0 Nepomniachtchi,I 
(2714)-Korobov,A (2687)/Jerusalem 2015/CBM 166/[Krasenkow,M] (46)}) ({and} 
12... e5 13. dxe5 Bxe5 {Black stopped e4-e5, but not for too long.} 14. f4 $1
Bxc3 (14... Bd4+ 15. Kh1 h6 16. Nf3 Bxc3 17. bxc3 c5 18. c4 $1 bxc4 19. Bxc4
Bb7 20. e5 {[%csl Gc4,Ge5,Gf4]} Nd5 21. Qf5 $1 $36 {[%csl Gf5,Rg8] and white
was getting ready to attack:} Ne7 22. Qg4 Bd5 23. Bxd5 Nxd5 24. Rd1 Qc6 25. f5
$40 {1-0 Bukavshin,I (2657)-Mikaelyan,A (2448)/Yerevan ARM 2015/The Week in
Chess 1092 (33)}) 15. bxc3 h6 16. Nf3 c5 17. a4 $1 bxa4 18. c4 $16 Bb7 19. Bd3
$16 {[%cal Ge4e5] 1-0 Boruchovsky,A (2501)-Iovcov,V (2224)/Batumi 2014/EXT
2015 (35)}) 13. Kh1 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Ge4e5] The threat of e4-e5 remains, this
time cutting off the bishop from the queen.} c5 $1 {Black sacrifices a piece
for several pawns and exposed position of white king.} ({Another version of
this idea is} 13... b4 14. e5 bxc3 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. g3 $1 cxb2 17. Qxb2 Bxg3
18. fxg3 Qxg3 19. Rf3 Qe1+ 20. Kg2 c5 21. Rf2 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Ge2,Gg5][%cal
Ga1h1] where black has four pawns (!) for the piece, but white is about to
fully consolidate and bring his pieces into the game.}) ({Black can still save
the bishop with} 13... h6 14. Nf3 Bf4 {but after} 15. e5 Bxc1 16. Raxc1 Ne8 17.
Ne4 Bb7 18. Qb3 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Gc5,Gd6,Ge4,Re8] he would have to suffer in a
really passive position, for which an extra pawn is a small consolation.}) 14.
e5 cxd4 15. exf6 Nxf6 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gd4c3,Rc7c2] We reached a very sharp
and unbalanced position, where black seems to be doing great. But we need to
dig a bit deeper:} 16. f4 $1 {[%csl Rh2]} Bg3 17. Qd3 {[%csl Gd3,Rg3][%cal
Gd3g3] getting out of the pin and attacking the bishop at the same time.} dxc3
18. Qxg3 h6 19. Nh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3f2] This is more to the point than Nf3 as
black would like to install his knight on e4, so this way white can easily
challenge it with Nf2.} Ne4 ({Black can also complete his development with} 
19... Bb7 {and after} 20. Qxc3 Qxc3 21. bxc3 Ne4 22. Re1 Nxc3 {we get an
endgame where white can fully consolidate his scattered forces with:} 23. Bd3
Rfd8 24. Nf2 b4 25. Bd2 Rac8 26. Rec1 $14 {[%cal Ga2a3] and black is in for a
long defense of worse endgame.}) 20. Qe3 Bb7 21. Nf2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rf2e4]}
Nxf2+ 22. Rxf2 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Rc3,Re6,Rh6] After the exchange of powerful
knight, white can definitely count on advantage. We analyzed this kind of
position in Repertoire against Classical Slav, where white's extra piece has
more potential than black's extra pawns.} Rfc8 23. a3 Qa5 {[%cal Gb5b4] Here
in the game 1/2-1/2 Yilmaz,M (2582)-So,W (2779)/Kocaeli 2015/CBM 167 Extra (54)
} {white had, among others, an attacking option in} 24. Bd3 $5 b4 25. f5 exf5
26. Rxf5 $40 {[%cal Ge3g3,Gc1h6] The position, of course, remains sharp, but
white's chances should be preferred.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "Ekaterinburg"]
[Date "2016.03.04"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Semi-Slav"]
[Black "CHAPTER 10: 9...b5 main line"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D46"]
[Annotator "GM Kuljasevic, Davorin"]
[PlyCount "43"]
[EventDate "2006.03.11"]
[SourceDate "2016.01.25"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O
dxc4 9. Bxc4 b5 10. Be2 Bb7 {currently stands as the most promising variation
for black against the Anti-Meran. Black players have been able to obtain
equality in this variation more often than in any other variation, mostly due
to the fact that black is ready to play c6-c5 really fast, sometimes even at a
cost of a pawn. Among many possible continuations, I would suggest the
following one:} 11. e4 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Ge6e5] The only drawback of Bb7, as we
already know, is losing control over f5 square. Pushing e2-e4 is therefore a
logical follow-up in order to provoke e6-e5.} ({In practice black have
acheived good results in all of the following variations:} 11. Rd1 {[%csl Rf2]}
Qc7 12. e4 (12. Bd2 b4 13. Na4 c5 14. Rac1 Rfc8) 12... e5 13. g3 (13. Bg5 exd4
14. Rxd4 Ne5 15. g3 Bc5 16. Rd2 Nfg4) (13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nd4 Neg4) 13... Rfe8
14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Bg5 Neg4 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Gd6c5] We can see that in
virtually all of them the move Ng4, attacking the f2 square, becomes
unpleasant for white. Therefore, I have decided to omit Rd1 (keeping the rook
on f1 to defend f2) and play e4 immediately.}) 11... e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 {[%csl
Gf5][%cal Yf3d4,Yf3h4]} {Here the only question is how to approach f5 square.
After many hours of analysis I have come to conclusion that perhaps the most
popular way via d4 is not the most promising. Instead I suggest a road less
travelled:} 13. Nh4 $5 {[%csl Gb7,Gf5][%cal Gh4f5] If you remember, the same
idea was employed against early dxc4, b5, Bb7 plan in CHAPTER 9.} ({Initially
I wanted to recommend the line} 13. Nd4 Neg4 14. g3 {which has been a real hit
lately} {mostly because many players were all too happy to grab a pawn with}
Bxg3 ({However, it is quite problematic to find advantage for white in the
line that starts with} 14... Bc5 $1 {[%cal Gc5f2]} 15. Nf5 Re8 16. Bf4 Qb6 $13
{[%csl Rf2][%cal Gb6f2,Gg4f2] which should not be surprising given that black
was doing well by attacking the f2 square in all the other variations. Quite
recently in two high level games: Wagner-Shirov and Nakamura-Giri black have
